subject: Appwrite‚Äôs Free Plan is changing - This might affect your projects
mail:
Hey there,

We‚Äôre writing to inform you about an upcoming Appwrite Free plan change. Starting September 1st, 2025, the Free plan will be limited to two projects per organization. Projects will never be paused.

This decision wasn‚Äôt easy, but it‚Äôs crucial for us to continue building and evolving Appwrite as a sustainable platform. I want to take a moment to share the reasoning behind it and reaffirm our commitment to supporting developers on our free tier.

Why we‚Äôre making this change

Let me start by saying: pricing is hard.

From the beginning, we‚Äôve tried to walk a careful line, offering a robust, generous, and accessible platform while building a business that can stand the test of time. After 18 months of pricing for Appwrite Cloud beta, we‚Äôve concluded that we need to make some changes to ensure Appwrite can grow sustainably, serve you for the long run, and accommodate growing infrastructure costs.

At the same time, we still fiercely believe in the power of free. That‚Äôs why we‚Äôre keeping Appwrite‚Äôs Free plan incredibly capable - so you can go from idea to app without hitting limits on the features that matter. All the core building blocks of Appwrite, Databases, Authentication, Storage, Functions, Messaging, and Sites will remain available on the Free plan.

What does this mean for you?

If you have more than two projects in your organization, you‚Äôll have full access to all of them until the 1st of September 2025. After that, you‚Äôll need to reduce the number of projects to two or fewer, or upgrade to a paid plan. 

You can pick which ones to keep right now in your Appwrite Console.

To make the transition easier, we‚Äôre offering free credits worth $30 for three months to help you explore your options and avoid interruptions.

You can add this credit code when upgrading: free2

Upgrade now ( https://link.userlistmail.com/c/940b6d6ddc633b7ab69181b1aca3dde1e12791d82dbfe3b9afbacb2378b457de624427d4e45c7f576b517e5d42ea24eb2ec3cc0d2bf3aac192527af115e0c7507158136a3e352c439c9b4c8cb7935facebe09890f9e5c5f386dbedf1dddac029 )

The code is valid until the 1st of September.

Keeping Appwrite sustainable

We built Appwrite with the help of the open-source community for all developers, from students to enterprises and everything in between. Ensuring that all developers can benefit from Appwrite will always be our priority. Appwrite‚Äôs Free plan will continue to provide the tools you need to start building real apps, without compromising on core capabilities.

We‚Äôre deeply grateful for your support and trust in us. These changes are part of our effort to ensure Appwrite can continue to grow alongside you and help you bring your ideas to life.

If you have questions, need help planning, or want to discuss custom needs, please contact us at billing@appwrite.io. We‚Äôre here to support you through the transition and ensure you can keep building without interruptions.

Thank you for being part of this journey with us.

Happy coding!
Eldad Fux
Founder & CEO

@eldadfux ( https://link.userlistmail.com/c/940b6d6ddc633b7ab69181b1aca3dde1e12791d82dbfe3b9afbacb2378b457de624427d4e45c7f576b517e5d42ea24eb2ec3cc0d2bf3aac192527af115e0c75095ab66620e14b0f143b3595b600061f70e5ad9b49543e81603c3e84477ef702d )

A gut-wrenching problem we can solve https://gatesnot.es/46dhnpT 

https://gatesnot.es/46dhnpT  

By Bill Gates https://gatesnot.es/46dhnpT| July 22, 2025 

It‚Äôs not the most glamorous topic‚Äîbut it‚Äôs the reason I got involved in global health.

Back in 1997, I read a Nick Kristof column that stopped me in my tracks. It said diarrhea was killing over 3 million people every year, most of them kids. I sent it to my dad with a note: ‚ÄúMaybe we can do something about this.‚Äù That moment helped launch the Gates Foundation.

Since then, the world has made huge progress. Childhood deaths from diarrhea have dropped by more than 70%. Rotavirus vaccines went from costing $200 per dose to about a dollar. Over two billion people gained access to safe drinking water and sanitation. Millions of kids are alive today because the world refused to ignore this problem.

Tragically, nearly 350,000 kids under the age of five still die from diarrhea every year‚Äîfrom diseases we know how to prevent or treat. And cuts to global health funding are putting that progress at risk.

We‚Äôve come a long way since that column in 1997, but the job isn‚Äôt finished. You can read more about what‚Äôs worked, what‚Äôs in the pipeline, and why we can‚Äôt afford to look away on Gates Notes now https://gatesnot.es/46dhnpT.   

Thanks, as always, for being an Insider.

subject: 5 Powerhouse Speakers. 1 Link. This Thursday.
mail:
Hey there,
¬†
This past Sunday, we hosted a Backyard AI Social in SF with Luke, the founding engineer at Cursor and he dropped straight heat.
Chill vibes, smart people, and convos that went way beyond the usual surface-level stuff.
¬†



¬†



¬†
Couldn‚Äôt make it? Don‚Äôt worry. We‚Äôve got a virtual guest speaker event this Thursday, and the lineup is insane.

Here‚Äôs who‚Äôs speaking:

Virtual Event: Thursday, July 24th, 2025 @ 5:30pm PT / 8:30pm ET
RSVP on Luma [https://lu.ma/mo2arpr9] to get the Zoom link
¬†
 1. Kunal Adhia is currently a core team member at Titan, bringing extensive expertise from roles at companies like Two Sigma,
    Apple, Amazon, Nvidia, and Capital One. He‚Äôs a UC Berkeley alum with a history of scaling developer platforms to millions of
    users and building high-performance infrastructure under intense loads.

 1. Ebrahim Alareqi serves as a Principal Machine Learning Engineer at Incorta, primarily contributing to large-scale ML
    engineering initiatives. His background blends deep technical skill and product-minded execution in data and AI systems.

 1. Efe Akengin is a venture-backed AI founder and product leader with over a decade of experience building real-time, agentic
    systems and foundational AI infrastructure. He‚Äôs an MIT graduate who‚Äôs successfully raised $25M+ to empower developers in
    shipping complex LLM-native applications.

 1. Mohammed Nasir is an experienced ML engineer based in the Bay Area and is a co-founder of General Agency (YC w‚Äô25). Graduating
    from MIT and bringing experience from Nvidia,his background includes advanced work in human-computer interaction and ML at
    major tech companies, now driving agentic AI innovations.

 1. Ankur Jain is currently an investor at Pear VC, where he focuses on backing AI startups at the pre-seed and seed stages.
    Before that, he built an edtech platform that scaled to over 70,000 users and led product efforts at Verily (formerly Google
    Life Sciences), where he worked on tools to combat opioid addiction. His work sits at the intersection of impactful technology
    and thoughtful early-stage investing.


Whether you‚Äôre building something new, figuring out your next step, or just want to be in the room with smart, curious people, we
got you covered.¬†

RSVP here [https://lu.ma/mo2arpr9]
¬†
See you Thursday,
Yasin

subject: The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud: July 22
mail:
The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud By Richard Seroter  
<mailto:rseroter@google.com>

New and shiny

Your agents got an upgrade with the new Vertex AI Agent Engine Memory Bank.

Our interactions with agents may span sessions and extend for some time.  
You‚Äôve had to solve this with your own state solutions. But with the new  
Memory Bank, you get a managed service that ‚Äújust works‚Äù for agents running  
in Vertex AI Agent Engine. See the blog post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rv4Ywxxu_L3yWSzRLregx8VVR8jzBjrxtlLFMYQ6OjwdrGkEivE-ghoyfNmvqYuXPrYCUcOOKp00cHoEJHW-4Hj_ADlvOKsV97pIyeUDT_Us9baWsyvrS-OleV2dE5H0m0E-6C69I9lLW1j9CNM1cJUgApUIVHgbO2PbUALHzRZ4e8KmnrIiSRyyhvIjPugLma9lAK3u0Lki6Fz4ODjRcwdSnA3Kc-92yUmb7YagRjNdA1>  
and docs  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pPl6eKnJNxKhtv2tHe-YbIgFbIrhPTquQu1PTYv3S5Jpi7A8My6WZR3Jih0qXHKSFqJ5QifB4nUvoWWBDbSkSL87ZZ3hIK2rM1w2y5B3b4_RnSuJrVelWbQf5hnxhQFgVnUxLl0zGH3Xm4fEwU-eD5LDf7klWdZpCK9tvhd-UNhIiS5Hnz1rImXsFJpa4niSDb_zln5UdCEIEG2whummyBMCwu>  
for more.

BigQuery gets some powerful new aggregation functions.

This won‚Äôt appeal to all of you, but to those dealing with rich data sets,  
this might be a BIG deal. These three new categories of aggregation  
functions  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pkPt08F0vUB3kLPaXIS_iLHDEFTwMTRc-Ssl5_Nrk3Wa_2UddAWH1XiRoXL8dPKOA6AI5q6h_Xr_HNRAwh6VhHW5g58sKIes8MRNHvZ76VCumM8DflH6aeVr7Zc6NWPH1LmaalXLp9qu--bng5WReiMrP8ief3IPk8c_yjEVtcvpxo3fFGUbZpqqTE49yK3kpmdKtoFGA__qRZ1hd4rXAh0NP70tYV5F3w-P1hdRnKO-O2zQIVdaKkIiniN8dFqWGDvINFoDd5IQEatOkP>‚Äîgroup  
by extension, user-defined aggregation functions, and approximate aggregate  
functions‚Äîmay introduce massive performance and efficiency improvements.

Cloud Run introduces worker pools and new Docker integrations.

How do you deploy a background task that continuously chomps on work? Now  
you can run these in Cloud Run worker  
pools.<https://c.gle/ANiao5rdoAe1BbADMjWRaCiZrscJy5W1N-2WqJ5DRcO5sk0Nj35nvNQGqoyKF3GlICNJWSP2ZCWgYNs3R0_RHwdWKgvmKkAaoh7NkIkdn1DN8ivXOrg_q8ZV9EFKYWUz6gI7el0wrRZDBFwvzvDf-8gm2PAllQo4HbO4G37a846H745BqF46d95vUVD8qlg2i9ehk_8>  
It‚Äôs great for processing data from Apache Kafka, and we also introduced a  
new open source Cloud Run Kafka Autoscaler.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oJMQUL15496DQTLfl1934GadHf3pP2oAoWrbn8XoI7Xt9ijHkDZVNG80d9wkQj7HU6SvZMG6IKVdGHW7fuXxx-YwKJ6FKl3epT6SulXHYqZxecjMzu_qqYL0md35zzlk1j7qIf2T6HMUBL86rfgIoE2vhzoal-Ozn-Pr28Iw4Jp_IFGv28dDO3e-YMlMBVeyKOt5S6NAQrKloXIKFB6s6r_63_JwJ8K8F9A_elxgMx1lbkfDybUoDswCJt1w>  
We also shared new integrations that make it easier to deploy Docker  
Compose definitions to Cloud  
Run.<https://c.gle/ANiao5oeiX2Diz4XX7bWfqitrZ521j4aKnwp9ukYX-scmUNppqTNpqqNxCQrLADrBBd8Nwju0Oj6CNRz5bMWMw07_r9CLWlMRRDCn_yqeNzxb7j_fVCUPrZm5xJNLYTHBJfJxrsj2AJUDikJsEQ2XKB_4gBONSN-n9I_ejY3wVfzV4-BUx2UmFBVDaAcETU7zbBZCshkPACxLCh0Q02k2nArInpgSXqqY5qPXTMbP7P7P1k9kCxDxCel7CjadagDCStjvz1BbLSKL1XtwhuvWwmM>  
Dig into all this new functionality.

Watch this

Take a fun tour through agent building tech.

Here‚Äôs an excellent video that uses great imagery and code to clearly  
explain concepts like agents, tools, and MCP.

A captured graphic of a Google Cloud video where Megan is explaining the  
types of tools that ADK provides to agent builders.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rq8o-IYGdkpf4Tg8wc0zsF-xiUYXPPRAT5F1ikAbKr4u-ck0VkIl6wJZ9YiZ-vbLc-FbtFTSIr50f495nOzpb-2QG-pSZfNvbktzdR7HdgTdtPbsjN916wAeKDm9KaKpKIIOo_2XRr6E8lLaZ3dTFlFJ9wGIZPBg>

Community cuts

Send emails from Google Cloud using the Application Integration service.

It‚Äôs true we don‚Äôt offer a built-in managed email service. But you can  
still send emails directly from your cloud apps using the Send Mail task  
included in the Application Integration service. Learn more in this blog  
post.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5p3uCYbSaVyFieAsM-GBFN4oQ7Pan7F8W7Qep_f5yr1TsJnxtcE0xEVDuyUmiGHiv_AE9J5KKYL-_euL8rBxnxPnKi3vOier5cgbJPWvClveyzfEDlCGaAOnf4wZilwic_Q3a-Uuq0l7Q7BvJvqG6yd3VGoBYLnS6R-usiarakGqKV_z831VNqO4-Yt5E91agtueRsjiewcbFW4H-fHXCyNXJshnbdLEkeA3PSmrQEbzclMlM16OsUC9GGQcd_s4KBysLU6n0R_wPFaLqGgu7gZaim_tz3eHcYRc4K9B9vE9axxVw>

Which service mesh is right for you?

It‚Äôs the age-old question: managed service or run it yourself? We give you  
both options in Google Cloud. Rahul and Shrey compare the managed and  
unmanaged flavors of Google Cloud Service Mesh.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5roSANjdWYIRayaHOxFRPenPzegjGDrmdnBPQHEa-ALIy-oEt5KdKel0Zyioq00hZY2h9ntTcEmWjHk1fOHl8b1gag5X1qFEn2CS0csJf32gnmRnznCT_hrrZIIPBUGSXrLfd8QLReFYNGIAuZjyHFjmOhkPpgtO0JNsbKvH2BouarYWwrhmAwR8A2wPKX_1dp9NKw7DnuMQOEqFglO1lMFutFzQ2WBx123lIY1sKMP97hzBGejqvVfcI7Y2PTnpH3vJhYYhlwkjZiHFgy4oaFp-h5-om88OJpb7G9bEhV9m6_wkk-cOUR_buil2eFCl-xQQcEu8HeoqaU>

Building and evaluating ADK agents.

Our friends at W&B wrote up a good look at the Agent Development Kit  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5r09thcMaV0s8SNrPIMULSdleM7sC2U3tg6H0qy24BdEOA-ikk0IEwn2W_xSrfSHtGYaQ7hvylsU96otZ__pqLqryc6Og7M5ULa7ZlzrbSgDdrBnQBR5aM11Wtbvqqf6qX04CHhMhCebdv8LheToXZeeKpsjp-jgBkLaVReumAW3gQiBFSLadKcZ6_bg5WpRn7j5PWrdFkTyxH2ro_rW2ftkGSfZD2LNikMFiHl3d-3RWFeF-V0l_aVBTrMYl8VT2_YfRCg_KSjJu0lOW-3lzynwHNjR9Z6yR1SxFC_yXdIYbsOHFdXGWHW87V7VA>  
and how you can trace their behavior.

Learn and grow

Try out Cloud Run worker pools by running this code lab.

We recently added this functionality to deploy continuously-processing  
background workers to Cloud Run. This code lab walks you through creating  
and using one as a Cloud Pub/Sub reader.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pzj4vJ-f1Qg7fTCr4NbRoA-1DpwltlkUObGdp1cGEJdCcs2PChcNBTFeNC-vD6W3aX_yna2Ojr_hfGF4oriY_0MeQiKebn2-8_bLtJV7mkGF3yjbznuQYsnaBDMN25LeBHG4GypNEVw5DSbLCQumBGpNibMK7epyGFz14d5ZnuyCr5x0N1vt-yYdBz2rZlhaQ7O_SK-0DmVA4FKblO3iRc3y4CPV_G2cBUn5LeN5UWGmzVXvdXF9jSzlyIDJolENVdFG6kHr1LDpxtNweqxNiPVb5ejI1G3tKLypq8gLzSUJI>

Build intelligent agents with the Agent Development Kit (ADK).

Today, we published a new course in Google Cloud Skills Boost for  
developers ready to start building their own agents with  
ADK.<https://c.gle/ANiao5ozD7McG8hLiTLCmnPyZUhnfEa8IQCpRDUxGrZVLa0ki4R4xhKNstdWeizudtRkQbhftJQmE97R6JA9wquG67fa64GGfownPu7ejXbjxpZZYHZpdMbijM5pa_6zwxTizVg7FIfoxcjCGV1D-FMAAl8V00IpDNpToYDjEYpg2yOI_eLzYP-vnemzoAx_U6l4LsZEah3CInBxtkqpD4qmiViSNJNx7AufdeKTaPlrKN47uPk4tVLK>  
It's packed with hands-on labs, core concepts, real-world applications, and  
resources from Google Developer Experts (GDEs) and the broader developer  
community.

Protect your (BigQuery) data from eager AI agents.

Here‚Äôs a great post with good tips for creating lines of defense around  
your BigQuery environment  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5p3UZcINlda3MHvBhx1bRWic-M7L921BDE9tl_5-hsMVNsWCYcMQrAMqiE1fqJP_RGOv6zgc_SeJ2GB1DHACOaup3P2gM9QtKxRKR1cfqBXGAWxBQeZ511dXSo8xWpsdJZsme0XDUieFj9eEnx7c4Qdg7MGR5KYLF1JzdePFSIwadQE6rNqfL0RJFfchAD1E_iOpS4ithxolPn99driQkIeE7CBKQu8ilf2dhzJnA75vZxWzrxLsasNC_Nhpdp4Ptll-kXQNQKdIQ2SE3IbvAhCnvuDwpaCx6jSF9sJqW-nwu9xxfEu7IP00JqTY0vfUluJ>  
to ensure agents don‚Äôt do too much, at too high a cost.

Get smart(er) about Google Cloud networking.

It‚Äôs hard to be good at Cloud without some working knowledge of networking  
configurations. This quick reference guide  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rQpBRVuIRZF56dPQvrQ2HqJaYmaAHut0D3fBchUHK0HmfLYKMyTENzf5cFnbzIfxIc550qbdiOh5tP7NL00BdCW8F4ZaZQMjobWdmnlmRlG5_0_Iy6Ix4Tpw4Iv2FyfTzmRHX1sRr0x4Kt9pAC2JCRf5iqEWnQdoPnbOpy4lVXSi_Kd88H7KhiopKdQIO8HGuUx0trypTfgWIbHViu6JqZ5DWCs5aXGAVEpxTg_FJkYgY_UDwtBDfcEUENUQHsdBi2j8XCQf-J4oRWsQ>  
points you to assets that help you learn more.

Set up a GraphRAG setup with Vertex AI and Spanner Graph.

If you‚Äôve got graph data that you‚Äôd like to ground your AI applications  
with, you might explore the GraphRAG option. I like this new comprehensive  
architecture guide  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qcdN_otCJbUCAYoNY1g3v_p1bKgzp61jsrgPvZiXMFtx8X_SmpvcSPZ-w3PYRRMAHqTZN57hlP4lCxIIn_KDkunCqhdO79RQNNWB9dqvJyCxLe_2SmAUTYXQx4QR7r15Ad9qzESrJzR0mKiGG9iUrHV6c8CsdPbfBQqO1JAnSjGHWdMY84oGe9sRqdLutc6Lx8k24CK9iC1YSFKiNx4nIDbGgbLw>  
that helps you configure this on Google Cloud.

Building production-ready AI Agents?

The Agent Factory video podcast dives deep into design, build, & deployment  
on Google Cloud. The podcast covers code, architecture , & practical tips.  
Subscribe now! ‚û°Ô∏è https://goo.gle/theagentfactory  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5ri_vyStCTlPQ5sCROaonIR1l19kVI-JCuZVhXZm_fH6GgXDmz-VuTmMUVtacQ9iZcx7mdLFy_YRMjHkOfk9LujTE8-ds8Rdtf7jdfGlf-UL5y6uZdoJPFllJo2Xiu4Q7pxOXbAxJEVx2DVwrLqiFcvX5XdJf3ajQ>

One more thing

Batch mode comes to the Gemini API.

Large jobs where you don‚Äôt need an immediate response? The new Gemini API  
Batch mode  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oJoQt9TyMqJFpNqTLrG5Rw3-3lCnYfs-yCx9wXd1DljQ4esbCBrtgevavE1tC1xHPkbt6iYqyw7w0DxjcBJkB5UiW-uL2OQg_UjeUs4JNaisuypQjMJgUy3BNNoWEeUkFsurpgSUyLAKVIeIAg6jMWPng1JOeBGhJDacxDiBVZ7UEhBqEd_8uI2Mzx1cDEnJivSZo_p8Ko0j-3T_JuoSSW5ukPbCvwmfsnmRDySPQ>  
returns results within 24 hours, and is half the cost.

An X post from Logan announcing the new Batch mode in the Gemini API  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qn0AVbcGv5IppIqB8lRdaHELUuQBqvTV-7_9bWrHgNyQrTibEWN-GryZaRyM7LMs0h2cXfuFV0H-WhcOfY2UhFLk6nGGaMWYdC66iJ4NWR7BRhePyfboEiMJApKkBl6VG9I38b2_hu6fHMevDB2exu8gnLwUDv4qedWdslsRlfJOJdgbcrOQ>

Follow us on Social media.

Add your voice to the conversation and get the latest news, views, and  
insights.

X  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qI0EX9saR71N2kRISPP45gbqjjZ7XKZOEzmVB2tLVqIJpbu5iiWe6lo6C4ZzmPaSWG_eDSGxiFfyQfGFvg44ryEKuoyNpeuwlcGTH-wZL5fkhlfqFURH_1B-yZfGjPmXQMAjZog29NHGrMIozUgcI01h9HLVH3A6zmZyqUKv1SXsvWjZqwHK7gJ1S6oTk>

Google Cloud blog  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rkUpGXr5CY7KM69Wb7wjnjrFINfG139OC4rMFqfxIvlAGmy1k_T-Pf5VH_zkZaFSUacGna-L7q-UM21J7CKY0SmCBqKDMxl7aYqiNneanHmLI4o8rFx3UNwU4VbsEE>

LinkedIn  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5q9rMqViKjJVFmHySZXgpOkGpht0yULamZ8ZSRV6l2jY6XQWWVDKqpBdM41itCqSpLCbA-QKq9rB8NwQO83D8xJHSM7vsynRBGdbHWMYSmPXimM22PaENQm0JffWTYvZdg_bAzsW4yQDhS1QSlN8v-Z3xfE>

<https://c.gle/ANiao5rupQBTTFty5pS59V9PuN1vJb0LyqolKGWDFgMtDQPCy-4Icy2rvmS7EhM1b922EnlimbOOWrP--n75iOpK6rOpAirqnfJPYqj79MywrSH29szz4SJz_lwj4sowO16rPBtZbEXTMrOZop0>

YouTube  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rZFPp6sJzVTWIeF1gVbik9Xy7e9TyjjBTD-B-DuiMJBCJD-TqjIIXY_tacwRlYukV5rB6xjdYjhFngsbvgFAYa9SD5567sfa__alcKBgFNmu_Gi298kCKIN2-GOcyMA92YrkC70fA5WfUbElQmtw>

GitHub  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qFDjLHUYnefaCBDXUkHIzbRuspzDHGAVRGgzci2c8vXyGY5SoysB1gCxTH1HCV3izrKd7RJqe6TiZFqou0s4-iZ4p0QABYWnzNannBgGkMoSqgU9u4c1yZQ2Np2j4YhIHITC-genCQYg>

** November 28, 2025 - London, UK
------------------------------------------------------------

Hi HUZAIR2024,

This year, TechLead (https://techleadconf.com/london/?utm_source=GitNation+Conferences&utm_campaign=7ae38d95fa-TL25_launch_cfp%2Beb_15%2F05%2F25_COPY_01&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_-788ab96665-568319264&mc_cid=7ae38d95fa&mc_eid=UNIQID) is landing in London for the first time! üé°

This special edition, ‚ÄúAdopting AI in Orgs‚Äù focuses on how engineering leaders are integrating AI across teams and systems.

Our agenda covers:
* AI in organizations: From AI-powered development workflows to cross-functional enablement, hiring, and measuring ROI.
* Managing system complexity: Scaling architectures, legacy systems, cognitive load, and the impact of AI tooling.
* Career growth: Transitioning to staff roles, growing into leadership, and becoming a key contributor.
* AI in Production: Lessons from teams integrating AI into products and workflows. Not what‚Äôs possible‚Äîwhat‚Äôs already working.
* Reducing Complexity: What senior engineers and managers are doing to keep systems understandable as they scale.

You‚Äôll hear case studies from fast-moving startups and large-scale systems alike. We‚Äôre curating talks from people who‚Äôve made hard trade-offs and can speak to what actually happened.

The Angular Custom Profiling Track is now available


Profiling web applications can be a complex task, often requiring developers to juggle between different tools that present data in disconnected ways. Traditionally, Chrome‚Äôs performance panel is excellent for detailed function call analysis, while Angular DevTools offers a higher-level view based on framework concepts like components, lifecycle hooks, bindings etc. Unfortunately, having two separate tools leads to a fragmented understanding of performance.


This fragmentation presented a significant opportunity to improve the developer experience when profiling Angular applications. As a result, the Angular and Chrome teams have partnered to bring Angular-specific data and insights directly into the Chrome DevTools performance panel, creating a unified profiling experience. We‚Äôre excited to introduce the new custom track for Angular in Chrome DevTools.


This integration allows developers to combine the benefits of both tools, offering a more synchronized and comprehensive view of their application‚Äôs performance.

TypeScript‚ÄØ5.9 Beta brings features designed to streamline setup, boost performance, and align with upcoming ECMAScript specs:

 * Stable --module node20 A fixed Node.js‚ÄØv20 resolution strategy (--module node20) models Node‚ÄØ20 behavior predictably, unlike the evolving nodenext, and implies --target es2023 by default.

subject: Only a few days before the 2025 Boot.dev Hackathon!
mail:
A contest for the ages

( https://www.boot.dev?utm_campaign=website&utm_medium=email&utm_source=sendgrid.com )

Greetings again, Huzair!¬†This is your reminder that the *Boot.dev Hackathon is THIS FRIDAY!*

*Friday, July 25th 9* *:00 AM -* *Monday, July 28th 9* *:00 AM*
(Mountain Time)

With the Hackathon imminent, we wanted to let you know how the winning entries would be decided. Once the Hackathon begins on Friday morning, you will have until Monday morning to complete your project. Here's a quick overview of the format:

* You can work in groups of 1-3
* If anyone in your team has held a (paid) job as a developer, you'll compete in the professional category rather than the amateur category
* All submissions must be submitted before the deadline at 9AM on Monday in the proper Discord channel.
* Submissions have two parts: a link to your project on GitHub, and a link to a social post (platform doesn't matter) announcing your project to the world
* You are NOT allowed to write any code that makes its way into your project before the kickoff event on Friday
* There is no specific theme for the hackathon - you can code whatever you like. One of our goals is to give you the chance to knock out your capstone project or personal project in the learning path
* The project must be easily installable and runnable in under 5 minutes with clear instructions provided on the README
* There will be a voting system for participants to vote on other students submissions, this will determine the top 10 in each category. The top 3 will then be selected by hand by the Boot.dev team.
* Prizes for the top 10 are physical commemorative coins. Top 3 winners will also receive letters of recommendation.

If you have friends that are interested PLEASE INVITE THEM. Get your bannerlord achievement and help make this event even more exciting! Following the submission deadline, there were be a brief recess while the winners are determined, and the *winners will be announced at Noon on Monday, July 28th.*

You'll need to be a member of our Discord Server ( https://www.boot.dev/community?utm_campaign=website&utm_medium=email&utm_source=sendgrid.com ) to participate (that's where we'll run the event) so join now if you haven't already.

Finally, *use the link below to add the event to your calendar* so you don't forget to join us in the Discord on the day of for the kickoff!

Add Hackathon Kickoff to Calendar ( https://calendar.google.com/calendar/event?action=TEMPLATE&tmeid=N2V1bzV0NWx0Nzk3NXZlY2xicm9vMDh2bWIgaGVsbG9AYm9vdC5kZXY&tmsrc=hello%40boot.dev&utm_campaign=website&utm_medium=email&utm_source=sendgrid.com )

With even more considerable excitement,
Boots

P.S. If you want to become a Boot.dev member before the event starts, you can use code *HACKATHON2025* for 25% off your first year on an annual plan.

Boots

3520 N UNIVERSITY AVE , Provo ,  84604

subject: üéì Become a GitHub Campus Expert
mail:
View this post on the web at https://recodehive.substack.com/p/become-a-github-campus-expert

Hi Everyone,
Are you passionate about tech, building communities, and making a difference on your campus? Then this is your chance to shine again! üåü
Note! This newsletter is intended to bring the latest updates, like the campus expert program, and help you to become the next leader in scaling up communities, having coding skills alone won‚Äôt help to secure a job in the coming years due to the AI, Agentic times. Working in this kind of community helps you build people skills.
In the last post, I discussed about Google Campus ambassador program. [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3c80e74-3916-4c33-b607-864871a1841c?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ] Here we gonna discuss about GitHub Campus Expert program. This is pure community info updates, and I personally verified the program is directly managed by GitHub and Google. 
The GitHub Campus Experts Program empowers student leaders to build and support technical communities at their universities. As a Campus Expert, you‚Äôll gain valuable skills, collaborate with GitHub, and help shape the future of developer education. 
üöÄ Why Apply for GitHub CE Program?
By joining the Campus Experts program, you‚Äôll get:
üéì Training in leadership, communication, and community management
ü§ù Support from GitHub and access to exclusive resources
üé§ A chance to lead initiatives, host events, and amplify tech learning
üåç Global recognition as a GitHub Student Leader
‚ú® My Story: From Applicant to Campus Expert
Over 8,000 students applied to the GitHub Campus Experts Program in 2021.
Only 84 were selected in this round.
I‚Äôm incredibly humbled to be one of them. üôå
This wasn‚Äôt just a form-and-done deal. The application process is intense and highly selective‚Äîonly 250 students globally have become Campus Experts in the last five years. Applications open just twice a year‚Äîin February and August‚Äîand the process is designed to deeply understand who you are as a leader and a changemaker.
üìù What the Process Looks Like
Application Form:
I had to reflect on the real challenges my campus community faces and explain what kind of opportunities I want to build for my peers. This wasn't just about accomplishments‚Äîit was about vision and community impact.
Video Resume:
After clearing the form, I was invited to submit a personal video answering core questions:
Six-Week Training:
Now begins the real journey‚Äîa six-week intensive training in:
üó£Ô∏è Public Speaking
üß† Community Analysis
‚úçÔ∏è Technical Writing
üßë‚Äçüíª Software Development
üìù And most importantly, crafting a Community Proposal
Swag time üéÅ
Upon completing the 6-week training, you will get swag from GitHub üëáüèª
This program isn‚Äôt just about prestige‚Äîit‚Äôs about learning how to serve, lead, and build something lasting in the developer ecosystem. And for that, the form was everything‚Äîyour chance to tell a story that matters.
‚úÖ How to check you are Eligible?
To apply, you must:
Be at least 18 years old
Be a GitHub user for 6+ months
Be enrolled in a formal higher education institution
Have at least 1 year left before graduation
Be verified through the GitHub Student Developer Pack [ https://substack.com/redirect/3e58275a-31f2-4926-aa29-dac18cc68123?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
Not enrolled in the GitHub Campus Advisors Program
üìù How to Apply for GitHub CE
Step 1: Submit an Application Form
Go to: education.github.com/campus_experts [ https://substack.com/redirect/76fbcb44-cb9e-4398-a4e5-aa2f2edd3b49?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
Click "Become a Campus Expert." [ https://substack.com/redirect/ec335f8a-11a9-4ce3-aa3a-3c68db2ceb90?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
If applications are open, click "Apply Now" and complete the form
Submit before the deadline (Applications open in February & August)
üí° Tip: Highlight the challenges your student community faces and the opportunities you want to create.
First process is very you are a student, so you need to enable the GitHub Student Developer pack for this. Watch this video to learn how to apply the Developer Pack and get verified. [ https://substack.com/redirect/3e58275a-31f2-4926-aa29-dac18cc68123?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
Step 2: Submit a Video Resume ( Once you have selected on Step 1) 
After your application is reviewed, you'll receive an email with instructions
Record a simple webcam video sharing your story:
Upload your video through the link provided in the email.
‚è≥ Timeline
üóì Application Opens: February & August(Every Year)
üì© Submit Form: Within 1 month of opening (ends in Aug mid)
üé• Submit Video: 2 weeks after the form closes (Sept end)
‚úÖ Final Decision: 1 week after video submission (around Oct end)
So, overall it will take 3 months to get your application reviewed by November of this year, you will get updates about your final selection and training.
üí¨ Need Help?
Have questions or accessibility concerns? Reach out to the GitHub Education Team or reach out to me via LinkedIn. I opened my DM for this.  [ https://substack.com/redirect/2bda5a5c-aa50-4882-8cbd-19c082b0335d?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
üì¢ Be the change your campus needs. Start your journey to becoming a GitHub Campus Expert and build a legacy that inspires hundreds.

üëâ Applications are open soon. Be ready!
üì∫ Video Resource
‚ñ∂Ô∏è Watch: Learn more about the Campus Experts‚Äô journey through this video seriesüëâ YouTube ‚Äì GitHub Campus Experts Overview [ https://substack.com/redirect/1f432e88-af9c-4812-9992-3e67061dcf4e?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
ü§ù Join Developer Communities

üëâ Request to Join [ https://substack.com/redirect/535fcdf8-ca3a-4e6d-8b06-494a2579566f?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
üõçÔ∏è Swag & Goodies
üõí The GitHub Shop: Get official GitHub swag and merchandise
üëâ thegithubshop.com [ https://substack.com/redirect/bce271d7-2391-4e3f-bd62-a4bb8ca82f9e?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
One More thing ‚ú®
I‚Äôm happy to provide a free GitHub profile review for a limited people. You can go the the mentioned link  [ https://substack.com/redirect/932fdc42-a62e-4d1f-b52e-816b3369d703?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]and apply coupon code ‚Äúrecode50‚Äù to get the session free (Only 50 free 50 Slots available).  This profile review can help you get personalised feedback on improving the GitHub landing page and get selected for the Campus Expert Program
Stay tuned‚Äîand never stop building.

 In the upcoming Newsletter, I will provide more details.
Google has launched the Google Student Ambassador Program, a national initiative to bring the power of Gemini AI to college campuses across India. This is your chance to lead the AI movement, represent Google at your university, and join a growing network of student leaders shaping the future of tech.
üéÅ What‚Äôs in it for you?

As a Gemini Student Ambassador, you will:

Spread Gemini AI fandom across your peers.

subject: Contributor to Community Leader
mail:
View this post on the web at https://recodehive.substack.com/p/contributor-to-community-leader

I want to share something close to my heart‚Äîmy journey in the developer community and why it changed the course of my career (and life). It‚Äôs been a winding road, from a Software Engineer to a Data Engineer and now a Program Manager.
Why is being part of a developer community so important?
It's simple: we're stronger together. Communities are where you find mentors, collaborators, and friends. They are places to learn from others, share your own knowledge, and get the support you need to grow. Below is the screenshot of one such community invite I was part of in 2016. 
This changed my course of action. Click on the image to learn more about it. [ https://substack.com/redirect/56690eb7-1b4e-4e58-b673-8962e7c01edf?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
From Contributor to Community Manager: You can do it too!
My journey from a contributor to building and managing open-source communities wasn't an overnight success. When I first made a pull request on GitHub in early 2017.
It started with small contributions, a willingness to learn, and a desire to connect with others. Here's how you can start your own journey:
üí° Join platforms like GitHub, Discord, or Reddit focused on your interests.
üõ†Ô∏è Contribute to beginner-friendly projects (check out good first issues [ https://substack.com/redirect/e3dc5fc3-eed7-4fd2-b8ed-4a61550fd2ee?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]).
üå± Attend or volunteer at local hackathons and events.
ü§ù Connect with people. You don‚Äôt need a title to make an impact‚Äîjust intention.
üåü Your effort today might be someone‚Äôs inspiration tomorrow.
I've always believed in the power of open source and the incredible things that can happen when people come together to learn and build. That's why I've dedicated so much of my time to being a Google ML Facilitator and a former GitHub Campus Expert. 
It all started with a single contribution: just a pull request, a few hours of my time, and a curious heart üíñ. I had no idea that this moment would open doors to incredible opportunities‚Äîmentorship, leadership, and friendships that transcend borders and financial freedom.
It All Started From a University Campus üéì

The answer is YES. A thousand times, yes.

I became a GitHub Campus Expert and a Google ML Facilitator
I gave over 100 talks on Machine Learning, Open Source, and Developer Advocacy
I mentored and taught over 100,000 people in tech
I was invited to Google‚Äôs offices in California and Singapore
I discovered freedom‚Äîintellectually, financially, and emotionally
And most importantly‚ÄîI found my tribe üåê
Then this happened, one invitation to the  California office and the Singapore Office.
‚ú® From Student to Global Tech Ambassador
My journey into developer communities truly accelerated when I was selected as a GitHub Campus Expert and later as a Google Explore ML Facilitator.
As a GitHub Campus Expert, I completed 6 weeks of training on diversity, inclusion, and open-source leadership. I organized events across Australian universities, empowering students to contribute and collaborate on open source.

subject: IRL: 3 cities. 6 speakers. One unforgettable week.
mail:
Hey there,
¬†
Join IRL and remote events this week with top 1% startups and top 1% investors. All for free.
¬†



NYC RSVP [https://partiful.com/e/yvJe7HNOEZbSXUmGzw0r] (7/17 Thursday) | SF RSVP [https://partiful.com/e/OZtI2y2u8Ogmu4VgII22]
(7/20 Sunday)
¬†



Can't make it IRL: RSVP [https://lu.ma/7v9rgtbc] Virtual event
¬†
From coast-to-coast and online, you‚Äôll hear from the minds behind breakout startups like Rilla, Coframe, Medsender, and Delve,
along with investors from a16z and pioneers like Nihal Mehta, who backed companies like Uber, AdMob, and Brightwheel before they
were household names.
¬†
Whether you‚Äôre curious about building with AI, raising VC funding, or scaling past $40M ARR, these speakers have been in the
arena.
¬†
Here‚Äôs what‚Äôs happening this week:
¬†
 1. Virtual Event: Thursday, July 17 @ 4:30pm ET

RSVP on Luma [https://lu.ma/7v9rgtbc] required to receive Zoom link
¬†
a. Nihal Mehta: A five-time founder turned prolific angel investor, Nihal backed companies like Uber and Brightwheel before they
were household names. He‚Äôs known for spotting breakout founders early and helping them scale fast.
¬†
b. Robin Guo: Partner at Andreessen Horowitz focused on interactive apps and consumer AI. Previously led investments at Riot Games
and worked in strategy at McKinsey.
¬†
2. In-Person Event: Thursday, July 17 @ 6:00pm ET
New York City, NY
RSVP on Partiful [https://partiful.com/e/yvJe7HNOEZbSXUmGzw0r] required for location details
¬†
a. Chris Martin: Founder & CTO of Rilla Voice, an AI company helping field sales teams close more deals. Rilla hit $40M ARR in
under 3.5 years and is backed by Bessemer.
¬†
b. Mahmoud Tohmaz: CTO of Medsender, an AI-powered health tech startup built on the most secure fax platform in medicine.
Medsender recently raised a $5M Series A.
¬†
3. In-Person Event: Sunday, July 20 @ 6:00pm PT
San Francisco, CA
RSVP on Partiful [https://partiful.com/e/OZtI2y2u8Ogmu4VgII22] required for location details
¬†
a. Josh Payne: CEO of Coframe, a Generative UI platform for enterprises backed by Khosla Ventures, HF0, and the CEO of Replit.
Before this, he exited three startups, including one co-founded with Tom Brady that raised over $200M.
¬†
b. Selin Kocalar: Founder & COO of Delve, a YC-backed startup building AI-native compliance tools. She‚Äôs known for bold,
unconventional campaigns that have earned serious attention in the Bay Area and beyond.
¬†
These events are free, but space is limited. If you‚Äôre exploring what‚Äôs next, thinking about building, or just want to be in the
room with great people, this is where you‚Äôll want to be.
¬†
See you there,
Yasin Ehsan
Co-Founder, Headstarter

From doubt to brilliance: Andrew Thomas on the secret to contagious creativity

Take a moment to explore Andrew Thomas‚Äô, creative head at Google Retail Design, journey and intriguing creative philosophy. In an emotional and engaging session, Andrew discusses the importance of belief, collaboration, and respect in nurturing successful creative ideas. Drawing from personal experiences, both in design and overcoming challenges, he emphasizes that belief in an idea is essential for its contagious power. When shared, challenged, and iterated upon, ideas evolve into something truly special.

Andrew also highlights the value of diverse perspectives in creative work and the need for feedback that respects and nurtures (rather than dismisses) ideas. Through stories of resilience and the importance of honoring both ideas and the people behind them, Andrew‚Äôs message serves as a reminder of the profound impact belief and collaboration can have in the creative process. Creatives should be encouraged to trust themselves, share ideas, and build them together.

Ever felt like life hit the mute button on your dreams?

We're thrilled to launch our very first episode of ‚ÄúThe Comeback Code‚Äù ‚Äî a podcast dedicated to helping you reset, recharge, and rise when life feels off-key.
Our debut guest? None other than Omar (aka Afro Trance) ‚Äî a Sydney-based DJ, who is a creative powerhouse with roots in Morocco and dreams louder than beats at a festival.
In this powerful, heartfelt conversation, we dive deep into:
üöß His rock bottom moments ‚Äî and the bounce back.
üé∂ How music became his therapy and purpose.
üí¨ Real talk on toxic positivity vs staying grounded.
üßó‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Turning setbacks into setups.
üîÅ Daily self-talk and mental rewiring.
üí° Advice for anyone feeling lost, rejected, or stuck.
‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt need to be positive all the time. You just need to be real, and keep moving. The rest finds you.‚Äù ‚Äì Omar
This isn‚Äôt your typical motivational chat ‚Äî this is raw, real, and relatable. Whether you‚Äôre navigating a breakup, creative burnout, or career detour, this episode is your frequency reset button.
üéß Life‚Äôs Offbeat? Hit Play on Your Comeback.
Job rejections. Unexpected detours. Nothing going as planned?
This podcast is for you. Tune into Omar‚Äôs story of setbacks, self-talk, and starting over ‚Äî and find your rhythm again.
With rhythm & resilience,

subject: A surprising bestseller about tuberculosis
mail:
Here‚Äôs how John Green turned a forgotten disease into a #1 NYT bestseller.https://gatesnot.es/3U4OQvk  

A surprising bestseller about tuberculosis https://gatesnot.es/3TACVFn 

https://gatesnot.es/3TACVFn  

By Bill Gates https://gatesnot.es/3TACVFn| July 15, 2025 

John Green is the author of beloved young adult novels like 

**The Fault in Our Stars** and 

**Turtles All the Way Down**. But with his latest release, he‚Äôs written a very different kind of book.

In 

**Everything Is Tuberculosis**, John makes the case that you can‚Äôt understand the past, or the world we live in today, without understanding TB. From its influence on fashion and furniture to its role in sparking World War I, TB has been everywhere.

This book is more than a history lesson, though. It‚Äôs a deeply human story about the kids who still suffer and die from TB‚Äîand the lucky ones who survive against all odds. One of them is Henry, a boy John met at a TB clinic in Sierra Leone. Henry‚Äôs journey through misdiagnosis, drug resistance, and grueling treatment shows how hard it is for children in poor countries to get the care they need. It also shows what‚Äôs possible when they do.

I‚Äôve known John for over a decade, since he traveled with me on a Gates Foundation trip to Ethiopia. I‚Äôm not surprised he wrote a book that makes people care about something they didn‚Äôt think was for them. I‚Äôm amazed, however, that he managed to turn a book about TB into a #1 

**New York Times** bestseller.

John calls this book 

**Everything Is Tuberculosis**. I‚Äôd call it one of the more compelling arguments I‚Äôve read for why global health matters and why we need to keep investing in it.  

You can read my full review of the book on Gates Notes now https://gatesnot.es/3TACVFn.   

As always, thanks for being an Insider. 

https://gatesnot.es/3U4OQvk

AI-Generated Protein Shows Promise Against Antibiotic-Resistant


A team of Australian researchers has developed a synthetic protein capable of targeting antibiotic-resistant strains of Escherichia coli (E. coli). The work, published in Nature Communications, was conducted using a local AI Protein Design Platform and marks a first for an Australian-led initiative in this area.


The research was led by scientists from the Monash Biomedicine Discovery Institute and the Bio21 Institute at the University of Melbourne. Their platform uses advanced deep learning tools to design proteins from scratch, rather than modifying those found in nature. The newly created protein, termed "de novo-1", binds to a heme-related target in E. coli, preventing the bacteria from acquiring the iron it needs to survive.

Brain Age Identified as Strongest Predictor of Alzheimer's and Death


A study led by researchers at Stanford Medicine has developed a method for assessing the biological age of individual organs using protein levels in blood samples. The findings show that differences in organ-specific biological age can predict disease risk and mortality more accurately than chronological age alone.


The work, published in Nature Medicine, used data from more than 44,000 participants in the UK Biobank study to analyze blood levels of nearly 3,000 proteins, some of which are known to originate from specific organs. The analysis covered 11 major organ systems, including the brain, heart, lungs, liver and kidneys.

Scientists discover the moment AI truly understands language


A new study published in the Journal of Statistical Mechanics: Theory and Experiment (JSTAT) reveals a piece of this mystery. Neboa - TypeScript Database


Neboa is a simple, yet powerful, type-safe NoSQL database library for Node.js. It is built on top of SQLite with better-sqlite3. It offers seamless data management with compile-time type checking and a seamless query API.

subject: LinkedIn monetisation is real
mail:
Here's what you need to do**Read time: 3 mins**

**In this week's email...**

60% of consumers see user generated content as the most genuine advertising.¬†

93% of marketers think it‚Äôs more credible than brand content.

Videos are booming on LinkedIn.

For those of you who notice details, you'll have noticed LinkedIn tested a TikTok / Instagram style swipe gesture for watching videos in the LinkedIn mobile app.¬†

It's recently been removed but it does not mean video is going away.¬†

If you're a viral video creator on Instagram or about to shoot your first video, some things you need to know to prepare you for trying out videos on LinkedIn.

- If your videos are doing way less performance than your regular posts, do not stop, because

1. All impressions (views) aer not equal. Videos are only counted after a minimal play time. This means 500 impressions on a video is more than 500 impressions on classic post.

2. Your audience may not be used to your new style, and may need time to adapt. Particularly if they are of a more analytical personality type.

3. Video is hands-down your highest-converting content on the platform. 84% of marketers say video increases sales.

It builds connection fast.

It shows your energy, your tone, your confidence all the things static posts just can‚Äôt do.

LinkedIn‚Äôs own data backs this up:

‚û°Ô∏è Video posts get 3x more engagement than text

‚û°Ô∏è You‚Äôre 5x more likely to start real convos that lead to business

‚û°Ô∏è 

**People buy from people** ‚Äî not from profiles.

Furthermore:

LinkedIn is taking a page from YouTube‚Äôs playbook and rolling out a way for content creators to monetise with "pre-roll" ads.

It‚Äôs a smart time to double down on your video game and grow your following now so you‚Äôre in a position to get paid for your content later.

This new feature is still in beta. It‚Äôs called Brandlink.

👉 Read more about it here https://www.linkedin.com/posts/wakeupmentor_linkedin-linkedinmonetization-brandlink-activity-7338837581154988033-3RAH/?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAABmKi5oB80R1Jr7RoMrbiuK_i-oB4xuTMPo

(And if we‚Äôre not already connected on LinkedIn hit that connect button. https://www.linkedin.com/in/wakeupmentor/ It's always a pleasure to meet our insiders.)

**Have you heard enough to be part of the 0.1% that is leveraging video?**
If you‚Äôre still overthinking it, I have something for you.

Our Content Conversion System‚Ñ¢ Course, especially how to use LinkedIn videos to 

**stand out** and 

**convert** in a crowded feed.

You‚Äôll get a clear breakdown of what‚Äôs not landing, why your content isn‚Äôt turning into clients, and how to fix it with simple, repeatable strategies that work in 2025 (not 2020).

P.S. The longer you hide behind ‚Äústill working on it,‚Äù the more momentum you lose.

This is your chance to move from 

**thinking about showing up** to

Let‚Äôs get your confidence up and get this ticked off your to-do list, for once and for all.

subject: B2B Offer Creation Complete Guide
mail:

Welcome to my full B2B Offer Creation Guide.
If you‚Äôre a B2B founder or marketer, then this guide will show you how to create amazing offers that your customers and clients love to buy.

Why you offer needs to be GREAT, not good
What a great offer is
The step-by-step process for creating great offers
What front-end offers are and why you need them
Why you should have a portfolio of offers
How to increase LTV with your offers
How to price your offer so your prospects say ‚ÄúYES‚Äù
The importance of the case study for selling your offer
Let‚Äôs dive in.
Before you jump into the guide;
I just published a complete LinkedIn masterclass with my method to blow up in B2B. Subscribe to the channel to get more videos like this.
And if you want to work with me, have a look at:

Plus, we help you on your social selling to close deals.

3. Sponsor this newsletter [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9c72145-1967-463a-92bd-3277270a1478?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]: Promote your brand to my audience on this newsletter (and possibly elsewhere). Send me an email at hello@pierreherubel.com
1. Why Your Offer Needs to be GREAT, not good
A weak offer can kill your business.
Weak offer = "I will think about it"
Great offer = "When can we start?"
When your offer is weak, three things happen:
You confuse prospects (and confused prospects never buy)
You get bombarded with objections in every call
Your revenue pipeline dries up
Far too many businesses sink time, money, and creative energy into marketing campaigns that just don‚Äôt convert well. And the reason for the failure is often not because the execution was off‚Ä¶ but rather the offer just wasn‚Äôt good enough.
That being said, in today‚Äôs saturated market, where generative AI has lowered the barrier to entry, even a ‚Äúgood‚Äù offer isn‚Äôt always enough to stand out.
The market is flooded with ‚Äúgood‚Äù solutions.
And that‚Äôs why you need a great offer.
Pierre's Content Guides is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Learn the 40-40-20 rule of marketing success to understand why offers make the difference
Let‚Äôs zoom out for a second and talk about where marketing success comes from. There‚Äôs a classic marketing framework that breaks down where your marketing success comes from:
40% comes from the prospect you‚Äôre speaking to
40% comes from your offer
And only 20% comes from the actual copy
That means the strength of your offer carries double the weight of the messaging you use to sell it which is what most B2B founders spend most of their time on.
Yes, messaging matters. But no amount of clever writing can save a bad offer. You‚Äôll have far more success selling a great offer with mediocre copy, than a mediocre offer with great copy.
So first we must ask ourselves;
2. What makes a great offer: Go from ‚Äúcommoditized‚Äù to ‚Äúproprietary‚Äù offers
Well let‚Äôs start with what a bad offer is:
A bad offer is a commoditized offer.
A commoditized offer is a service or solution that your competitors also sell and that can be found anywhere, without any USP.
Commoditized offers get objections like:
‚ÄúI can get it for 50% less elsewhere‚Äù
‚ÄúMy nephew can do that too‚Äù
‚ÄúOk, we‚Äôll pay you with a testimonial‚Äù
‚ÄúCan you remove Feature C to lower the price?‚Äù
These aren‚Äôt pricing objections. They‚Äôre red flags that your offer looks like everything else on the market. Commoditized offers allow prospects to compare you to your competitors. And most of the time, they‚Äôll default to the cheapest option.
Having a commoditized offer is a race to the bottom and an impossible way to grow your B2B business.
The solution to commoditized offers is to build Proprietary offers.
A proprietary offer is something only you can provide:
It‚Äôs built around your unique approach, process, or intellectual property.
It can‚Äôt be easily copied or price-shopped. 
That makes it high-value and high-leverage.
Proprietary offers have far more value than commoditized offers due to the Unique Selling Points (USP) they provide.
Think of it as the difference between being a service provider vs. being the ONLY one who can solve the problem THIS way.
Proprietary offers position you as the go-to authority. They change the conversation from ‚Äúwhy are you more expensive than X?‚Äù to ‚Äúwe cannot get this anywhere else‚Äù.
Your Proprietary offer should always start from this principle: You need to solve a PURE problem
The foundation of any great offer is that it fixes a PURE problem:
Painful: It genuinely hurts their business
Urgent: They need it fixed now
Recognized: They know they have this problem
Expensive: The cost of not fixing it is high in terms of money, time, or opportunity
When your offer solves a PURE problem, you will never have a problem with demand, nor with price objections. Now you know a great offer is a proprietary offer that solves a PURE problem.
Let me show you an example:
How I built a proprietary offer in my previous business and transformed a $500 offer into a $15,000 offer
I‚Äôve been creating offers for a while;
In 2018 I was charging $500 for landing pages.
Then I did ad account management for $400/month. 
Then marketing funnels for $1,500.
The problem was I was solving problems‚Ä¶ but with commoditized offers.
My offer wasn‚Äôt proprietary and so I was replaceable with any other freelancer who could do landing pages or marketing funnels. Everything changed in 2021.
Together with my business partner at the time, Alain Briez, we asked ourselves a single question:
‚ÄúHow do we create an offer so unique it can‚Äôt be compared?‚Äù
After a little testing, we came up with 3 month ‚Äúcommando mission‚Äù packages for $14,000 to $15,000, which allowed us to successfully scale our business up to $1M in just 14 months. We were testing marketing channels with weekly sprints for early stage clients (or big businesses that launch new projects).
The difference wasn‚Äôt just in our pricing. It was in our positioning, packaging of the offer, and the problem we solved for businesses. That‚Äôs what is possible when you ditch commoditized services and focus on building great offers.
3. Step-by-step: How to create a great offer
A great offer doesn‚Äôt start with your product, it starts with your market.
A common mistake is when B2B founders fall in love with what they can build, and not what their market truly needs.
The result? Offers that are vague, bloated, or irrelevant.
Here‚Äôs a step-by-step system to make sure your offer is one that people even want to buy.
Pierre's Content Guides is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Step 1: Start with the market, not the product, to anchor your offer in the context of your target audience
You can‚Äôt create a great offer in a vacuum.
Creating a great offer starts with listening to what the market is telling you they need.
This means gathering data from:
Sales calls and demos
DMs and inbound questions
Customer success conversations
Reviews of competitors‚Äô services.
You want to look for recurring themes. Are they struggling with conversion? Retention? Growth? What is it they‚Äôre complaining about?
Step 2: Identify the PURE problem at a granular level, not just ‚Äúthey want more revenue‚Äù
Now that you‚Äôve gathered the raw insights, you want to isolate the PURE problem affecting them. Remember, PURE means:
Painful ‚Äì It's a real limitation hurting their business
Urgent ‚Äì They need it fixed now
Recognized ‚Äì They‚Äôre aware the problem exists
Expensive ‚Äì It's costing them money, opportunity, or time
If your offer solves a PURE problem, you‚Äôre already ahead of 95% of the market.
Identify the PURE problem you could solve, then run it through step 3:
Step 3: Identify the 7 key factors of successful offers
There are 7 key factors that make an offer successful:
Factors 1 to 3: the foundations of your offer that promise an outcome
Factors 4 and 5: the efforts required for your prospect to access the promise
Factors 6 and 7: how you explain this promise
They are arranged from most important to least important.
For example, solving a very painful problem that has market demand will still bring in revenue‚Ä¶ even if the clarity of message or packaging isn‚Äôt the best. But that doesn‚Äôt mean you should neglect Factors 6 and 7.
Because it‚Äôs these elements that can help your offer stand out more and reach its full potential.
Step 4: Stack capabilities, benefits, features, and guarantees to increase the perceived value of your offer
Now you amplify your offer by stacking value:
Add bonuses that complement the core promise: E.g. A cold email software including 50+ proven cold email templates 
Offer guarantees that reduce buyer risk: ‚Äú5 qualified calls booked per week or your money back‚Äù
Include onboarding, audits, or fast-start elements to boost perceived ROI: Free data audits and roadmap workshop when you sign up
These are the accelerators that will make your offer more competitive.
Step 5: Test your offer, iterate based on feedback, and improve the most important aspects step by step
The first version of your offer will rarely be perfect. That‚Äôs okay.
The only way to know if it‚Äôs a good offer is to test it in the market:
Do a pre-launch or release it only to a small segment of your market.
See what sticks, what the market likes and doesn‚Äôt like, and what objections they have to buying.
When you have this data, go back to the drawing board. Revisit your PURE problem and the 7 key components to see what can be improved with your new feedback.
That is how you create a great offer. When you‚Äôre done reading this guide, I recommend going back and actually creating an offer using this method.
Now, let‚Äôs talk about one of the most powerful tools in your business:
4. Create a front-end offer to guide your prospects to an easy choice (and avoid decision paralysis)
Imagine your perfect prospect sees your LinkedIn post‚Ä¶ clicks on your profile‚Ä¶ visits your website‚Ä¶ and then‚Ä¶ they see three different service options with a dozen price points and the option for ‚Äúcustom‚Äù packages.
The result? Your prospect is overwhelmed with decision paralysis and they leave.
Now, let‚Äôs consider the opposite:
They discover your content ‚Üí DM you ‚Üí you guide them to one, simple, low-friction offer.
They say ‚Äúyes‚Äù quickly, get fast value, and become a highly qualified, warm lead for a higher ticket offer. That‚Äôs the power of a front-end offer.
What is a front-end offer?
A front-end offer is a simple, low commitment entry point into your world and portfolio of offers.
It‚Äôs not meant to be your main profit engine. It‚Äôs simply designed to:
Remove friction
Deliver fast results
Build trust
Tee up your main offer
Front-end offers should be:
Easy entry points: Make the front end offer easy to understand and solve a problem that your audience knows about.
Low-price point: Start with a lower-priced product or service to attract customers that won‚Äôt take a big risk.
Fast time to value: Make sure your offer delivers results fast (within 1 month) to hook the customer and move on to the next offers.
Front-end offers are also a great way to take advantage of the Halo Effect:
The Halo Effect is a cognitive mechanism where a positive perception of one aspect of a brand or product influences a person's opinion about the entire entity.
Essentially, you can have your prospects love your brand and become a life-long customer simply by overdelivering on the front-end offer.
By definition, front-end offers are just the beginning and lead to other types of offers for maximum LTV
After you‚Äôve sold and delivered this front end offer, you should move the customer through your next offers:
Middle-end offer: It‚Äôs the offer that comes right after the front-end. You upsell your existing customers to an offer where you will help them more, or for a longer time.
Backend Offer: For clients seeking more value, present a higher-tier offer.
For the first $0 to $300K of my previous B2B agency, we relied on an easy entry offer. It helped us to gain trust, show expertise, and onboard new clients.
We started with a $1,000 front-end offer
Upsold to a $12,000 full service engagement
Offered a $5,000 coaching track for those wanting a hybrid approach
When should you use a front-end offer?
You should consider a front-end offer if:
You're struggling to convert cold leads into clients
Your website or content ecosystem presents too many choices
You want to build a clearer path from content ‚Üí lead ‚Üí client
This strategy works especially well if you‚Äôre building inbound with content. Social content builds trust. The front-end offer harnesses it.
5. A portfolio of offers will allow you to increase LTV and revenue across your business (but only if you do it correctly)
You‚Äôre not in the business of selling one thing. You‚Äôre in the business of solving one core problem at different levels of readiness, urgency, and investment.
This is where the Portfolio of Offers comes in:
Instead of forcing every lead into your flagship service or high-ticket program, you guide them into the right next step for where they are.
It varies, but the general portfolio of offers can look like:
Why the portfolio approach works
A portfolio of offers lets you:
Capture more demand (across different budget levels)
Increase lifetime value (by moving customers up the value ladder)
Diversify income (with less dependency on any one offer)
Leverage your content (by giving readers a clear next step)
One problem, many levels
As you can see, all my offers help solve the same strategic pain point of ‚Äúcontent marketing‚Äù for B2B founders and marketers. But not all prospects are equal. Based on their level of readiness, urgency, and willingness to invest there is an offer available for them.
6. Install strategies to truly help your clients in the long term and increase lifetime value
A great offer gets the sale and a great system turns that one-time sale into multiple sales. If you want to build a sustainable and scalable business you need to optimize for Lifetime Value (LTV).
LTV is the total revenue a client brings over their entire relationship with your business. And when you increase it, you:
Can afford to pay more on acquisition (meaning you can outspend your competitors without affecting your profit)
Can scale faster
Have higher profit margins
Here‚Äôs how to do it:
1. Build continuity into your offers
Continuity is when your clients pay you regularly rather than just once.
Think:
Monthly retainers
Ongoing coaching memberships
Subscriptions to premium content or tools
Annual support packages or check-ins
By introducing continuity into your offers you reduce decision fatigue. They don‚Äôt have to ‚Äúre-buy‚Äù your value every month, it just keeps showing up.
A perfect example is a monthly subscription to a core offer. You can have people subscribe for years.
2. Extend the relationship lifecycle
Ask yourself;
‚ÄúHow can I keep supporting the customer beyond the initial engagement‚Äù.
For example, instead of a 1-month SEO project where the customer leaves your business after the project is finished‚Ä¶
You could try:
Offering quarterly strategic reviews
Provide a ‚Äúmaintenance‚Äù or support phase after project delivery
Create VIP communities for clients
Send early access invites to new products or content.
When you stop treating delivery as the end of the relationship and start seeing it as the middle, your LTV will naturally grow.
3. Make it harder to leave than to stay
The best offers don‚Äôt just retain clients, they create switching friction.
You want clients to think:
‚ÄúIf I cancel, I lose access to all those templates, reports, or frameworks.‚Äù
‚ÄúI‚Äôll miss the private Slack group and monthly strategy drops.‚Äù
‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to start over with someone new.‚Äù
This isn‚Äôt manipulation by the way. It‚Äôs simply giving them so much value through your offer that they won‚Äôt want to leave.
4. Move from projects to partnerships
Project-based revenue ends when the deliverable does.
But partnerships grow over time.
Ask yourself:
Can I shift clients from fixed deliverables to a rolling strategy (e.g. monthly funnel optimization updates)
Can I offer ‚Äúoffice hours‚Äù or fractional support after delivery?
Can I offer incentives for annual commitments instead of one-offs?
This changes your relationship from a vendor to a strategic partner.
LTV should be your #1 metric
It‚Äôs easy to chase the dopamine of getting new clients. But if you‚Äôre going to be in business for the long-run, the best metric for you to focus on is LTV. Always be asking yourself:
How long can I keep delivering value to the same person?
Because continuously acquiring new customers from scratch is one of the most inefficient business models.
7. How to price your offer so clients actually say ‚Äúyes‚Äù and you make good profit
(These advices apply more to service businesses than SAAS where pricing depends mainly about your features, competition, and unique selling point)
One of the most paralyzing questions for B2B founders is:
‚ÄúHow should I price this?‚Äù
Most look outward: ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the market rate?‚Äù
But smart marketers look inward: ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the outcome worth to them?‚Äù
Your clients don‚Äôt pay you for the amount of hours you put into delivering your offer. They‚Äôre paying to make a painful, urgent, recognizable, expensive problem go away.
It‚Äôs not: ‚ÄúWhat would they pay‚Äù
It‚Äôs: ‚ÄúWhat would they pay to never deal with this again?‚Äù
That‚Äôs value-based pricing.
The 5 types of B2B offers (with 3 pricing tiers)
There is no one-size-fits-all. But most scalable B2B businesses build around these five offer types:
Here are a few options on how to optimize pricing for LTV:
Sell a high ticket offer directly through a discovery call + sales process (good for services).
Add a front-end offer before the high ticket to cover your CAC (good for services).
Sell a product with a subscription and aim to increase the price (good for SAAS or community).
Build an "offer ladder" with a low ticket offer, an upsell to a back end offer, and then to a back end offer (good for courses + coaching).
If you're still hesitating, sell a front end offer now to gather feedback and add another offer next.
Key pricing principles of value-based pricing
1. Price based on value, not time: Your clients care about outcomes, not effort. Package the transformation your offer brings them, not the hours.
2. Anchor your price against the cost of inaction: What does this problem cost them per month in lost revenue, churn, or inefficiency? If you solve a $50,000 problem, a $10,000 offer looks like a bargain.
3. Give your offer room to grow: Start lean if needed, but build your pricing so that it allows for future upsells, tiers, and exclusives.
Remember: You don‚Äôt charge for what you do. You charge for what changes because of what you do.
I keep repeating myself, but only because it‚Äôs true: We solve PURE problems.
The more PURE it is, the more money you can charge.
8. Case studies are the bridge between your current clients portfolio and your next 100 clients
In marketing, proof will always beat promises. You can talk about your offer all day. But what prospects really want to know is:
‚ÄúWill it work for me?
That‚Äôs why case studies can often be your most powerful sales asset.
1. Show don‚Äôt tell
A case study demonstrates the outcome your offer delivers. You‚Äôve proven you‚Äôve gotten a real client, a real result.
2. Crush objections early
A great case study answers all these before they even come up.
‚ÄúWill it work for us?‚Äù
‚ÄúWhat kind of results can we expect?‚Äù
‚ÄúHow is this different from other services?‚Äù
3. Increase trust and confidence
A strong case study builds emotional and logical trust. It shows your offer isn‚Äôt just an idea, but a repeatable process with proven results.
4. Turn readers into leads
Case studies are the perfect lead magnet. They attract your ICP because they showcase the same problems and desired results your prospects are after.
How not to write a case study
Most ‚Äúcase studies‚Äù are just testimonials with a headline: ‚ÄúClient X grew revenue by 44%!‚Äù But that‚Äôs not a case study at all. It lacks context, depth, credibility, and believability.
A good case study will go in-depth about:
The client‚Äôs customer profile (so other prospects in that ICP can relate)
The problem that client faced
How your offer solved that problem
The transformation it gave them and
The overall takeaway others can learn from
When to use case studies
As a lead magnet to attract your ICP
As a follow-up asset after a sales call
On your offer landing page to boost conversions
In your email nurture sequences to build trust
As social content to create demand
If your offer works, you should be collecting, writing, and spreading as many successful case studies as you possibly can. I recommend even making it part of your delivery process by adding ‚Äòcase study collection‚Äô to your project wrap-up.
Now you know how to build a great offer that sells
You now have the full blueprint for crafting, pricing, and scaling high-converting B2B offers.
We‚Äôve covered:
Why a great offer beats great marketing
The difference between commoditized and proprietary offers
How to structure, test, and refine your offers step-by-step
The role of front-end offers and value ladders
How to increase Lifetime Value (LTV) through continuity and retention
How to price based on value, not time
And why case studies are your most powerful asset
If you‚Äôve made it this far, congratulations. You now know more than most B2B founders and marketers when it comes to offer creation.
Here‚Äôs What to Do Next
Audit your current offer: Is it solving a PURE problem? Rate it against the 7 key factors of successful offers.
Map your offer ladder: Start simple. Entry ‚Üí Core ‚Üí High ticket.
Create one strong case study: And use it everywhere.
Look for ways to set up continuity: Subscriptions, retainers, or rolling access.
Refine your pricing: Make sure you‚Äôre selling outcomes, not your time.
Great offers don‚Äôt appear out of thin air. They‚Äôre crafted using the process above, tested on the market, then iterated until they‚Äôre perfect.
Start building or refining your offer today. Trust me, once you have a great offer, the rest of your marketing, sales, and content starts working better.
Good luck,
Alright, that‚Äôs the end of this edition. Hope it will help you to build your offer!
Pierre Herubel

Gitpod Newsletter ‚Äì July¬†10¬†2025

July¬†10, 2025

********************************************************
AI wrote your code. Open source rejected it. Here's why.
********************************************************

00:00 | 15:40

*********************************************
The landscape has changed for AI development.
*********************************************

Last year, the main concern around AI coding assistants was accuracy, now it's trust.

Open‚Äësource projects are increasingly cautious about accepting AI-generated code, while new fees on data scraping are pushing teams to reconsider how they build AI workflows. Here‚Äôs how your team can adapt, keeping velocity high without compromising security or compliance.

TL;DR

‚Ä¢

ICYMI ‚Üí Ona early access: Privacy-first software engineering agents that run entirely inside your VPC. Rolling out to first users ‚Äì Request early access. ( https://www.gitpod.io/solutions/ai?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )

‚Ä¢

Code provenance becomes critical. QEMU banned AI-generated commits; traceable, auditable code is now table stakes.

‚Ä¢

Web scraping gets expensive. Cloudflare meters AI crawlers; keep agents internal or pay per request.

‚Ä¢

Memory makes agents reliable. MIT research shows structured memory boosts agent performance by 30%.

‚Ä¢

Join us in NYC: Learn about secure AI development at AWS Summit NYC on July 15. ( https://www.gitpod.io/aws-nyc-2025?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )

---------------
Ecosystem watch
---------------

QEMU bans AI-generated code ( https://github.com/qemu/qemu/commit/3d40db0bef22520fac399cf7396d0ced423b048 )
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Open-source maintainers at QEMU have started rejecting patches generated by tools like Copilot and ChatGPT, citing unclear code provenance and licensing concerns. Expect more projects to follow suit, making signed commits and clear authorship essential.

Cloudflare introduces pay-per-crawl for AI bots ( https://blog.cloudflare.com/introducing-pay-per-crawl/ )
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Cloudflare now charges for web scraping by AI agents, turning a once-free resource into a metered service. Keeping agents inside your infrastructure and using local data reduces compliance risk and cost.

Context beats prompts for agent performance ( https://blog.langchain.com/context-engineering-for-agents/ )
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

LangChain outlines four practical steps‚Äîwrite, select, compress, isolate‚Äîto shrink token counts, reduce costs, and improve the reliability of agent-generated code. Clearer context equals safer results.

Memory transforms agent reliability ( https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.00081 )
------------------------------------------------------------------------

MIT researchers have shown that agents with structured memory outperform stateless ones by 30%. By maintaining state and tracking progress, these agents handle complex tasks better and recover gracefully from failures. The takeaway: agents work best when their context and memory are structured, sandboxed, and auditable.

Developers are becoming orchestrators ( https://jamie.ideasasylum.com/2025/07/01/you%27re-all-cto-now )
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

As AI agents handle more coding tasks, developers find themselves managing code rather than writing it. Understanding and embracing this shift can help developers stay effective‚Äîand satisfied‚Äîin an AI-driven workflow. (P.S. we had similar thoughts ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/software-conductors-handbook?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email ) a few weeks ago).

-----------------------------
ICYMI: Launches & new stories
-----------------------------

Watch Ona close your GitHub issues ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wYTFJMefQCY )
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

See Ona autonomously pick up a GitHub issue, break it into subtasks, implement unit tests, and push updates, all while you focus on other work. From automated dev container configuration to complete test implementation with real-time GitHub status updates, watch how enterprise teams can multiply their engineering output without compromising security.

Real-world use cases for secure AI agents ( https://www.gitpod.io/ai-use-cases?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Here are 42 use cases from workshops we held in London and NYC with 100+ platform engineers to either inspire you‚Äîor deter you‚Äîin shaping your own AI roadmap.

The enterprise version of Codex just dropped (but it's not from OpenAI) ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/codex-for-enterprise?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Love coding with Codex on weekends but can't use it at work? Ona brings the same parallel execution and background processing to enterprise development‚Äîexcept it runs in your VPC with your choice of models. Jump between AI orchestration and hands-on coding in your preferred editor, while your security team stays happy.

Ona: Your privacy-first software engineering agent ( https://www.gitpod.io/solutions/ai?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ona runs entirely within your VPC; your code, credentials, and logs never leave your infrastructure. Each task creates an isolated, disposable workspace and returns small, tested code changes. Gitpod enterprise customers get priority access.

Gitpod-hosted compute launches this summer ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/coming-soon-gitpod-as-a-saas?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email )
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Fully-managed SaaS option with high-performance CPUs and GPUs. Get standardized development environments that start in seconds with zero infrastructure setup. Join the waitlist. ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/coming-soon-gitpod-as-a-saas#:~:text=Gitpod%2Dhosted%20compute.-,Feature%20waitlist,-Email )

Gitpod improvements for better security and efficiency
------------------------------------------------------

We've shipped three updates to strengthen your development workflows:

* VPC endpoints ( https://www.gitpod.io/changelog/vpc-endpoints?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email ) for secure internal network traffic.
* Organization-level secrets ( https://www.gitpod.io/changelog/organization-secrets-support-in-gitpod?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email ) to simplify credential management.
* Auto-archive and auto-delete policies ( https://www.gitpod.io/changelog/archive-&-auto-delete-for-environments?utm_campaign=newsletter&utm_source=customerio&utm_medium=email ) to minimize maintenance and control costs.

Dear learner,

You‚Äôve explored how foundation models like GPT-4o, Mistral, and Llama are built and used. Now take the next step: Learn how to adapt them.

Before a large language model can follow instructions, it undergoes two key stages: pre-training and post-training. In pre-training, it learns to predict the next word or token from large amounts of unlabeled text. In post-training, it learns useful behaviors such as following instructions, tool use, and reasoning.

OpenAI drops Scale AI as a data provider following Meta deal


OpenAI is phasing out its work with Scale AI and cutting ties with the data provider following Meta‚Äôs deal with the startup, an OpenAI spokesperson told Bloomberg on Wednesday. Sarah Friar, the chief financial officer of OpenAI, previously suggested the company would continue its work with Scale AI. Now, it appears OpenAI has changed its tone.


OpenAI said it was already winding down its work with Scale AI ahead of Meta‚Äôs announcement last week that it was investing billions of dollars in the startup and bringing on CEO Alexandr Wang. An OpenAI spokesperson told Bloomberg that OpenAI had been seeking other providers for more specialized data to develop increasingly advanced AI models.

DeepNVMe: Affordable I/O scaling for Deep Learning Applications


PyTorch introduced DeepNVMe in summer 2024 as a suite of optimizations for tackling I/O bottlenecks in Deep Learning (DL). DeepNVMe delivers significant speedups for I/O bound DL workloads by leveraging storage innovations including local NVMe SSDs, NVIDIA Magnum IOTM GPUDirect¬Æ Storage (GDS), and Linux Asynchronous I/O (AIO).


In this update, we are delighted to announce DeepNVMe improvements on multiple fronts:


 * Expanding application coverage to FastPersist model checkpointing and SGLang inference.
 * I/O performance scaling by upgrading from PCIe Gen4 to Gen5 NVMe SSDs.
 * Expanding usability to CPU-only environments, offset-based I/O operations, and tensor data type casting.
