subject: Do THIS and you'll never have to rely on referrals again
mail:
4 years ago, nobody knew my name.
=C2=A0
I was starting out as a freelancer, determined, but still unsure of how you=
 actually go about building a business online.
=C2=A0
But even then, in my early days, I felt like everyone else was doing things=
 wrong.
=C2=A0
People running ads on Meta to land new business=C2=A0
B2B business owners posting on IG (clearly trying to get new leads)
Specialists posting on LinkedIn, but talking about random, cringe content
=C2=A0
Here's the truth. LinkedIn is STILL the most untapped platform for scaling =
B2B marketing efforts.
=C2=A0
The platform has 1.2 billion users.
=C2=A0
1.7 billion monthly visits on average.
=C2=A0
BUT only the 1% who post good content weekly dominate it's entire market sh=
are for free impressions.=C2=A0
=C2=A0
That's not a bad thing. It means this platform is just waiting for the mark=
et to catch up and for those like you to take advantage of the insane growt=
h your operation could see on this platform.

I write from experience. **Read time: 2 mins**

Every day I get at least 5-7 DMs asking me:

"I want clients. What‚Äôs the first step I should take?"

And here‚Äôs what I tell them:

¬†if I was starting from zero with:

No website.
No followers.
No funnel.

Step one: Decide what the goal is.
50 Leads? 10 Sales? Top of Search? Thought Leader? Employees? Investors?¬†

Most people are not clear on the goal and then overcomplicate this, post, comment everywhere and burnout.

This is how the algorithm works, there's a hidden dashboard called the "Social Selling Index" and LinkedIn will show you what it thinks of you. (I've included the link to access the dashboard further down.)

But first ‚òù🏽

You want to aim for a score that is over 60/100 and at that point, the platform starts to push your profile.

Over 70/100 and you're likely in the top 1% of your industry worldwide, now your profile will begin to be "boosted" and this is how you can do it.

I want you to get over 70/100 and here's how you do it:

**‚Üí**

**Dial in your LinkedIn profile** ‚Äî Make it crystal clear who you help, what you do, and why it matters.

**‚Üí** 

**Post with purpose** ‚Äî Your story matters. But tell it in a way that earns trust and moves people to act.

**‚Üí**

**Create a solid offer** ‚Äî No guesswork. Just something people actually 

**want** and are 

**willing to pay for.**

**‚Üí**¬†¬†

**Master the DMs** ‚Äî Conversations turn into clients. If your inbox is quiet, your pipeline‚Äôs broken.

**‚Üí**¬†¬†

**Get around winners** ‚Äî Community matters. Get in rooms where people are making moves, not just talking about them.

And watch your score increase, conversations begin and calls get booked.¬†

That's a high level overview of the system you'll need to build.¬†

And if you‚Äôre feeling inconsistent, or invisible?

Here‚Äôs your next step:

**Do one thing bold today.**

‚úÖ Publish that post.
‚úÖ Send that sales message.
‚úÖ Ask that prospect if they‚Äôre ready.

Most people wait, but LinkedIn doesn‚Äôt reward waiters‚Äîit rewards 

**doers.**

If you‚Äôve been thinking about building something that runs even when you‚Äôre offline.

You‚Äôre in the right place.

And now, here's the link to check your score: www.linkedin.com/sales/ssi

Let me know what your score is, I'm intrigued to know..

Click here to get ONE step ahead https://calendly.com/linkedinbusinessacademy/ise

**LinkedIn Blindspot Call** is a zero-fluff strategy session built to expose what‚Äôs keeping you stuck ‚Äî and give you a system that actually works 

**in 2025**, not two years ago.

If you‚Äôre tired of watching others win while you‚Äôre still tweaking posts and second-guessing everything...

This call will change that.

And as I always say to my mentees, your profile is your pitch. Your content is the proof.

subject: Content Distribution: 7 Use Cases That Work in 2025
mail:
View this post on the web at https://pierreherubel.substack.com/p/content-distribution-7-use-cases

Hello welcome to this edition üëã
I talk a lot about content strategy and creation but distribution is equally important.
If your content is perfect but no one sees it, you are playing the wrong game.
Your audience won‚Äôt magically land on your ‚Äúresources‚Äù section in your website. That‚Äôs why you need a proper distribution strategy.
üí° Content distribution means sharing your insights where your audience spends time to maximize traffic.
So in this edition you‚Äôll learn:
The 3 most common distribution problems (and solution)
7 content distribution use cases that we use at ContentPath [ https://substack.com/redirect/be250651-8436-40dd-b3e7-cf80aaf9d1f9?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ]
The connection between content distribution and revenue (use case 7)
Introduction: How and why most businesses fail with content distribution
Most companies don‚Äôt have a real distribution plan. They treat their content as a rigid output while it should be an asset built to circulate, evolve, and repurposed.
Problem 1: Total imbalance in budget repartition
Most of the budget goes into production while distribution is treated as an afterthought. Everything is invested into design, writing, video editing, motion. But almost nothing is planned for distribution or paid support. 
‚Üí Solution: add a ‚Äúdistribution‚Äù line to your content strategy budget
Problem 2: Lack of proper system for repurposing and distribution
There‚Äôs no structured process to break down and reuse content across formats and channels, so every asset gets used once and then forgotten. One report could become 10 LinkedIn‚Ñ¢ posts, 3 infographics, 1 short video but it rarely happens. 
‚Üí Solution: put repurposing at the center of your distribution system
Problem 3: No consistency over time and across channels
Content is published randomly without a clear schedule or channel strategy, which makes it hard to build awareness or stay top of mind. It‚Äôs posted here and there, without rhythm or coordination.
‚Üí Solution: stay consistent with a long term content plan
7 content distribution use cases that we use at ContentPath [ https://substack.com/redirect/be250651-8436-40dd-b3e7-cf80aaf9d1f9?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ] (for us and our clients)
Context: ContentPath [ https://substack.com/redirect/be250651-8436-40dd-b3e7-cf80aaf9d1f9?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ] is my visual content creation agency. We repurpose our clients‚Äô knowledge and resources into highly visual content for LinkedIn‚Ñ¢. We‚Äôve developed specific distributing use cases that I will share here.
Use case 1: Repurposing Dense Reports into Infographics
Reports are often hidden in the ‚Äúresources‚Äù tab of websites. They get seen during a few weeks and then replaced by the next report. But they are often costly and full of interesting insights, so they need a better distribution plan. At ContentPath, we turn them into infographics.
How to implement:
Identify high-value reports already published by the company (e.g. white papers, research, internal surveys).
Extract 5‚Äì10 key data points or takeaways from the report (stats, charts, insights).
Group them by theme or narrative e.g. ‚ÄúMarket Trends,‚Äù ‚ÄúPain Points,‚Äù ‚ÄúSolutions.‚Äù
Work with a designer (with tool like Canva or Figma) to create infographics or LinkedIn carousels.
Publish them over several weeks on relevant channels (LinkedIn, newsletter, blog, pinterest, reddit, instagram).
Track which visuals perform best and consider using them in outreach, ads, or pitch decks.
Use case 2: Repurposing Webinars & Podcasts into Infographics
Webinars and podcasts are often shared once, then forgotten. They can be distributed natively on YouTube or podcast platforms but most of the times they disappear.
How to implement:
Choose a webinar or podcast episode with strong expert content (ideally evergreen).
Listen and timestamp the most valuable 3‚Äì5 moments (quotes, visuals, frameworks). This can be done with AI.
Summarize the key ideas visually: turn a framework into a diagram, or a quote into a quote card.
Create 2‚Äì3 infographics or carousels per episode to stretch distribution.
Post on social weekly, alongside short copy that gives context or invites conversation.
Optionally, link back to the full episode for people who want to dive deeper.
Use case 3: Distributing company news with a build in public angle
You cannot use the old school newsletter or LinkedIn post with ‚Äúwe have a new feature‚Äù and a static image that looks like an ad. This is perceived as salesy by your audience. But if you take the build in public angle, you are sharing the behind the scenes with interesting stories, that‚Äôs much better.
How to implement:
List upcoming internal news (product updates, hires, milestones, experiments).
Choose 1 story per week to document and share publicly.
Gather internal material: Slack messages, mockups, Figma files, quotes from the team.
Write a narrative post that explains the why, how, and what from an insider perspective.
Add a visual: screenshot, behind-the-scenes photo, or even a Loom explaining the feature.
Share on LinkedIn or X, tagging relevant team members if appropriate.
Optionally, save these stories in a monthly newsletter or blog recap.
Pierre's Content Guides is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Use case 4: LinkedIn Thought Leadership Ads
Companies often invest in expert content but don‚Äôt use it in paid campaigns. Thought leadership ads on LinkedIn offer a way to share useful insights (like a key idea from a webinar or a quote from a podcast) with a targeted audience. The best strategy is to ‚Äúboost‚Äù the best performing posts with this type of ads.
How to implement:
Select 3‚Äì5 pieces of expert content already published (webinar, report, blog post, internal doc).
Write short posts that distill one insight each: quote, observation, framework.
Post them organically on LinkedIn and wait 1 week to assess performance.
Pick the best-performing post(s) based on engagement (likes, saves, comments).
Use LinkedIn Ads Manager to ‚Äúboost‚Äù the selected post to a targeted audience (job titles, industries, etc.).
Run small A/B tests on headline or visual to see what lands best.
Review performance weekly and create a playbook of formats that work best for future campaigns.
Use case 5: Repurpose long videos for better distribution
Publishing videos on YouTube is already a distribution tactic because people actively search for topics on this video hub. But you can expand the distribution with additional tactics:
Turn long videos into short clips
Turn short video clips into ads
Include your YouTube video in your newsletter
Include the video in your linktree or email signature
Send the video in 1:1 messages
Publish a video teaser on LinkedIn or X
Use case 6: Run a case-study first marketing campaign
Case studies are often underused. They‚Äôre shared once on a website or in a pitch deck, but they can do much more. When used as the starting point for a campaign, they help build trust with passive buyers and offer strong proof for active ones.
How to implement:
Select one strong case study that reflects the kind of client you want to attract.
Break it down into multiple content pieces: a carousel (before/after), a short post on the challenge, a testimonial visual, a quote clip.
Publish the content over 2‚Äì3 weeks across LinkedIn and your newsletter to feed the content ecosystem.
Use the full case study in outbound efforts (LinkedIn DMs, email, sales calls) to prove results.
Include it in paid campaigns by promoting a carousel or testimonial to a lookalike audience.
Track engagement and replies to identify warm leads showing intent.
Use case 7: Connect your content distribution system to intent gathering and warm outbound
Your distribution system has a direct impact on your revenue because it determines how well you reach and convert both passive and active buyers. At ContentPath [ https://substack.com/redirect/be250651-8436-40dd-b3e7-cf80aaf9d1f9?j=eyJ1IjoiMm90dHY5In0.slPrdTexHAlV6GU1XsqSwzAtamrz67HqSEfMIqq0-3g ] we‚Äôve developed a methodology to contact relevant engagers and warm leads. I will give you an overview in this part.
Why you need content distribution in this system
1/Only ~5% of your market is actively buying right now. These are the leads ready to convert. If your system isn‚Äôt built to catch intent signals and act on them (with inbound or outbound), you‚Äôre missing direct revenue.
2/The other 95% are passive buyers, not ready yet. But they still matter. If you consistently nurture them through a content ecosystem, they‚Äôre far more likely to think of you when they do become active.
3/ So no distribution system = no visibility = no trust. Without consistent, multi-channel distribution, your content stays hidden. You lose the long-term compounding effect of being present in your buyer‚Äôs mind before they enter a buying cycle.
Content will primarily help this red area;
How to connect content and warm outbound
1/ Invest in an intent signals gathering system. To make the warm outreach more efficient, invest in an internal system to gather intent. You can combine engagement metrics, gated content interactions, website visitors, product analytics, external tools, and potentially AI.
2/ Run warm outreach for potentially active buyers. Some ready-to-buy prospects who like your brand may not contact you. They may be busy, forget, or assume you‚Äôll reach out. Acknowledge this reality and contact them directly. 
3/ Reuse your content for 1:1 conversations. If you‚Äôre creating case studies and posting on LinkedIn and your blog, that‚Äôs a good start. But if you‚Äôre not sending them to engagers or profile visitors, you‚Äôre using only half of the potential of your content.
The connection with outbound will happen in this green area;
Alright that‚Äôs the end of this edition! Hope it will help you to distribute more content.

subject: The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud: July 3
mail:
The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud By Richard Seroter  
<mailto:rseroter@google.com>

New and shiny

Gemini Code Assist in Apigee API management now GA.

Get AI assistance when creating or updating API specs, when getting  
summaries of API specs, along with testing and publishing APIs. Check out  
the blog post.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oYiZBgkQoG2m4zSSu7QLBeva_Jntd9cZLXMPv6kHu3rSae4kQpm7MO8HLClYfZkhaNKcmo8GQIZcPRIOfU8EZL4UcORYs2JC_DjjfMsCrQaoNAux-RgULJUaHmQ2RdC9o8pMrjRNiiVx5vcQ9es0b1fE5RTvRVyZGx9G_HDHyTT0o83wli23xZ9-nS3GlSOzTr4aZ66C1VjJAzu_wMqj27JbxDLfesszo2Dbaw7mGw-ytOyGTpGifauw>  
And if you haven‚Äôt looked in a while, Apigee is now almost fully integrated  
into the Google Cloud Console!  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oA78imDJL50KDvPE_PAi3tIGvBXrbAexT8lXOsYQLzvYbLQUvz05lIO94WoUVQmAQPQ4F3jR16MMlnGxbFn-swMXL7cs5eNBNoDnpc5DLDZnP4-5ZNZxwBze5nv6cQuIhMLviHVY2xhKDogac_lMjXIORhfH8ogXNC_hPK1clMcZms5LXP0ZJSi_gXyMX_I0NDbKCFNzUA9G7iipY3ltIPzUxIbW55WBoVRN8fSRoN1YyuEWKer_-PAWo>

Google Cloud Run gets GPUs for jobs, and IAM conditions on services.

These are both terrific. Add GPUs to your Cloud Run jobs  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oNy2na9gnMwYgv5AEEo0zaa5BzCBD6SNEjtszhH4N5EUeF9ihiTxUXB0b_ZlNPU56e3hpzfSajqnL1AT_QTDmqP4971gYXCb_-LOVbJiEgmFk3EopO7jUX1a2HM0FhLX5fdlTQjHSCKMiy_NdBzBuZFln7Av0Z6BhN6cCKnOYfzEvOcjrLtMy19uGqt-kO1znCrXPpkluE>  
to perform batch inference or compute-intensive work. For Cloud Run  
services, introduce IAM conditions  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pV2NuT0iT15oBKwwLlwIWI9ODZcmUa7H7GRIY8nWlPiOs5t8fsTcnoznzBw0iRgKWMr1B_tZ6o5TfAaa9Q_JSLWs50AN-M_OTKmG7prFzeGN_C8N8iHk7M2CBukOzuFH8GHAt_OtOVzln7Ck3V0vOYxgwtrsfwtNUjQtD9yWTQ7SsIC8sAlm8E5tBmRRoDTvrC-hjoILLCux7x55uCM7KWfGw0>  
based on the host and path to provide more granular access control.

New API for finding the right cloud location.

The Cloud Location Finder is a new service  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5psRZAxlyE_nnkDm7yk_vjpUeVACVl6tbTGxVBqIAL3msEhUyXfzpouvIj2rONOGNqU8Y6RISTqhYTZIXgCN8aXvdZFsmFsUFRWgTz9hCEFBJBbEgHFrhtlajQ9kjdtSmrP--nZZMq6ah7ZxoxzGj_jgBWxPy7Hasd7Xj6Tl6_wS2RRzZzHCL6sRCvvp_q9h9e701sWOpmW-0nYzLVXXckrS24aI_KxC5N5iKIOuJjMYMA2-beWC89dAnYtN3ov6DFWG6OVdKISRbHA9xGv1G1O876olCir>  
that lets you query an up-to-date list of physical locations across Google  
Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Oracle Cloud  
Infrastructure. The CLI and REST API makes it possible to bake this into  
your provisioning workflows!

Watch this

It‚Äôs time to learn more about Model Armor.

This cloud service might do more than you think! Aron does a fantastic job  
educating us about the top 10 LLM risks, and how Model Armor provides an  
extra level of protection.

A captured graphic of a Google Cloud video where Aron explains how to use  
Model Armor to protect an LLM-based application.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rjkQHBEu3oJNy2pwsr04-aTjLzUGuG6Vpy6IlAKedW9XvKCPm8cwgJGzJPqCJD5v7tUx34-L5VPT4Zs08_eY4QIo8uRubIMd6pCyzPTxVx0GroWLWhx88c_5bDZ664YYJn0a9bJ3m5Zz_-Ah9aMgCsvZ0Gy_fetw>

Community cuts

Let‚Äôs learn how to test agents.

I‚Äôm seeing plenty of cool content on creating agents, but not as much on  
the testing and evaluation aspects. Glen has a useful post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qYpoUVeuppAIspEIl2HzNZbqEqIDCFJyqJ3Mnh69DY2TOH2GsuAWLH-DPljetCw2Fyoo0RXnDzK712BxPunh1z7Q4MJkl3HAFAaKdUabVIN3F3J4HenbXlO412o3RdYq215l3Yy1cBy1gITSpxi0JvvLQbvukh13ztC3r-zEq9vUiUBlbo0bvwDwfQOIXB4dgrJM0ZJGN7k68vJwAMD0prk3lv2-L_LoMjpSK-kwHIdeJ0outXDVIhn1mso4k>  
that explains the built-in evaluation capability within the Agent  
Development Kit.

Make sense of your piles of data using BigLake.

Do you have a lot of instructed or semi-structured content you want to  
analyze? Aleksei explores BigLake  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pebGKj1hFZSUMy5npz_UYpL3OX_X2kla97ottrxnhxMjKQ7RVD2gyc2oPjPcrztBFEa5hDW8ERBpsh9YBcKCmuUc04Y9gV8XVa7ZcjVHHiQ_fQAREMGayAM838SGFJn2KYxevsX6Xk_-lvwP6WMKPbGsPrvj7_XtQEBNo68tVO2NFrMKwXWzoYfTNY_UmQdPnGJaZJ0ZHF_PchieMjc65NWpnpQoi_PCF0h0ycOUDNxGHdPd7ijXfMR9gwPx4ML7J6xP7Gk0z6vhFL_UN3pEnXTld-zyPojGfyX71SY_diLtgZ9uEuL2Acww>  
in depth and helps you set up a working example.

Another good multi-agent example.

You all are creating a lot of these! Krishna wrote a strong solution  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pgiE09ghjXXShoywh8CmHnnob3om7HnQyfx689D5YA9K-ollW3idzEnJX63A3iwpEidYPfOntIckKIIbpiM3aTdsHiqqNvBfZ9BQhjiNAPknwj2Bq7GIGspJ5SeKLML6rdFyWYiDmoxffHP1Qft3ZSyl9_ImpTzA8Pu-x1rd6PTTK1p8z12XTMv3O-ueXN0YMEYvEFagVqav2dZ_bMJxmV6iFMJMHQI5yHIfiX4ZHBVxD8DwST5yke_XpFAw-7AZYEwcG8Lnd-bhMootaO__Bb2g>  
that has multiple agents working together with the hemp of Gemini and MCP.

Learn and grow

Explore code for a full-stack research agent.

This repo  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qkZRWDjIcUzKIAUi_FwYJITBmLGz_omI2OeOPTX5NR2YhVNI7Re5x5m4X8kgpcXS4sN-fOFNnjQdC-w4-TvM13kSEes-tS_n2PvCumt-GuhLdULJxbZWn5Zdgyxe6J0b-ia-qtr8ucEv_bDO3y7IrkvLCNu6l2cxdgl7Ek8ccf3lIU5wCGEO2b3Q85PVSRH7UTD1BNL-lcqAdxVzIU984>  
contains a robust demo app that uses the Agent Development Kit, Gemini,  
React, and more to realize a multi-agent solution.

Run ML and AI workloads using our managed Lustre file system.

Lustre  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5ocucH5JdnyPjLT2BeH0fWaWzJa-wkssoldMmCgUa1LPFb8fJUPMc_kRlT3NP18k-AZZcVNQ17SuQVARpzPTk9n0Uli5EJST3oGrB1WkODviajB-ICAudUZMaAU-VRYFlCiCQnEBec>  
is a popular open source parallel file system. This new architecture guide  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5q2VXmmUFycseWrTe2vacw9_aqp-Zj08Hl2aU4BhRVvYngWNs0Y8a0fUosI15iFHiAU8ANJ59D_e_RHZD8GHVYfZGlSOiJ7ASyww8o1jzuslzv6IKySI1s4LiyEfPUoH9rzB4cQsaqLgFvq-Ms3_mFXkpRhIBEPBqFvmvGNsvWBhpUMvbaWKh0JQWKj3HGrJbhNKp3aBiZnYV-T8Z0fWNCI-2WF5xHUFZdoqqZZS-g>  
helps you take advantage of our managed offering while running AI and ML  
workloads on GKE. If you need high throughput and low latency, check this  
out.

We‚Äôre doing vibe deployments now.

You‚Äôre coding apps with vibes why not take it all the way to production?  
YOLO. Karl shows how tools  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5ovwxhHXxf7AYbt9sm2bW0GcYJJ4a3AAveiK4PcV-KjsgYmhF1iei1lXXvWS-Ghw2i2xOTnODC7LkIS_i6EcEoEHUtkMrGVSR1wMYHrb8CEdrnyXTZtjaNoxTdkyZPOEqZUD2ZQzE0ATNxsyxT42vmWJqvFjmhwBnjzsTMhj3gqYAgZm7jXwKJlwGQ1nbgnEfCETGEXQH5G2bW9IdVKrQH90vNn0pl2r8ucRh-NMCL0UG9sLLn1pCgz5w>  
like Jules help him get his working app all the way to Google Cloud Run.

Configure GKE rollout sequencing.

Have a series of Kubernetes clusters that you want to upgrade in a  
responsible order? This feature helps, and here‚Äôs a walkthrough  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5ovgY84DoO8HgXRg5Kk5ZnrJm5-kquf7VFZpIfkt7FYhJBYCpZVO-ylYnMA9kE1b4-C0gIBJDY9B6a3qVaBWh08BXPMxRQdiw7poQnz5SDxLohbkKKWjW8JB5bb_WulIFI-1Q9Yeb_3I0ARQkzebarmHeUzPhhUS_tWeBuPCJmpvhvWf88a7YH2JoxIYQ3vE0Qnm1XgVG_jE2sopxedLQ6qlFERQOdNdvQijxU8QLm9AyyPor2H2ATuSvu8h7pP3EiB8oo>  
of how to set it up.

One more thing

Gemini Code Assist is fun to use.

We‚Äôve been tackling usability friction for months, and here I talk you  
through a tour of why it‚Äôs never been a better time to use this AI coding  
assistant.

An X post from Richard that highlights many usability improvements in  
Gemini Code Assist.

subject: L.A.B. Report - June
mail:
It was my birthday recently and I sat down thinking about some of the lessons I've learnt so far. I decided to share them with you and create a special edition of the L.A.B. Report. I hope you enjoy it and let me know¬†your top life lesson!

If someone offers you an opportunity that you think is beyond your capabilities, they might know your capabilities better than you do.
When you feel the need to numb yourself of a particular feeling- sadness, shame, guilt, anger, it‚Äôs probably less damaging to set 10 minutes aside and just devote yourself to feeling that emotion than engaging in all the harmful coping mechanisms you‚Äôve developed.¬†
Sometimes the simplest path to happiness is just to do what you want to do, if you can do it.
When you brag about yourself, you‚Äôre also telling yourself that you-as-you-are, is not good enough for other people.
Asking yourself would I want a relationship with myself is a good gauge of how much you can accept yourself.
Life is often like a multistage video game, sometimes you get so good at the grass level that you refuse to learn new skills and still try to win the underwater level with the grass skills.¬†
When you feel stuck, move and change. Movement generates information.¬†
Knowing when to stop is harder than knowing when to start. Knowing when to sell is harder than knowing when to buy. Knowing when to quit is harder than knowing when to try.¬†
Life is a short lived VR experience, it‚Äôs better value for money to have more experiences than to only have good experiences.¬†
When making decisions you should optimise for different things at different ages. 
10-20: optimise for options that will result in more skills. 20-30: optimise for options that give you more options. 30-40: optimise for options that give you new experiences. 40+: I have no idea!
Two major types of relationships will determine your overall satisfaction at the end of life. Your relationship with yourself and your relationship with others. Try to find contentment in both.
Sometimes life doesn‚Äôt give you what you want, or worse, gives you what you don‚Äôt want. How you fare in these situations is a good test of how much you have used life to grow as a person. Many people stay at the tantrum stage well into their 60s.
Your brain is not evolved to deal with constant stimulation. Learn to see that boredom is an essential nutrient in a high-functioning brain diet.¬†
Anxious types usually have a good imagination, rather than catastrophising, try fantasising. They‚Äôre both not real, but one is more pleasant.
High performers usually use discipline as the very last resort.¬†
Game theory usually works well in life. Be kind first, and you‚Äôre more likely to get kindness back.
Travel not to see a different place but to find an alternative interpretation of ‚Äúa good life‚Äù.¬†
In life and in business, try to only do win-win deals.
Anyone you randomly approach anywhere in the world is 99% likely to be good. Anyone who randomly approaches you is 99% likely to not act in your interest.
Wishing you all the best,
Your instructor,
Angela

The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to AI with Google Cloud

by Chloe Condon  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qYQEpBS193fhPDJluz_XuYxfXLGSh72lgR3qLEkyWaJ7rHvLclqmG_aywyHWityt6wq-9LiDK0oUIt4RGt9VGqi1cHGb6OP-MR7-9B7a9Rim0zmz6v7IWo2ekmpdcnYXpA9bFgi3g6S7VIXq2Pr2VMgTuOVvRLZpGrcJbempYjkrhtdau_Pd3mABEfIcK-5w6TNpdw070x>

Hello again overwhelmed subscribers! Can you believe we are halfway through  
2025? Somehow I/O has come and gone, the confetti has settled, and the AI  
world still hasn‚Äôt slowed down. If you feel like you blinked, and suddenly  
missed 45 new product announcements‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre not alone! üòµ‚Äçüí´ Which is why  
I‚Äôm back in your inbox: to help get caught up and make sense of it all!  
Consider this issue a cheat sheet to get you caught up on all the  
announcements, and must-knows from I/O and beyond. Being almost halfway  
through the year may feel overwhelming, but we have some exciting things to  
share with you. June's almost over, so let's take a look at all that's been  
going on.

New and shiny

Highlights of new AI announcements

100 things we announced at I/O! üíØ

I‚Äôm a big fan of lists- and this is a great one to help you get caught up  
on what was announced at I/O last month! This blog  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oQEdzyVrdC0n3JkbXF-VJxoyGTh-cJr0e9jIJrrhpYD7Bnq1Dr4S0k8uXvr7Wvwvs4N70w9YaYYOHUrm8jwn7v3EuXsWIgnzacQktogp3AIT5ZHuOpIB69V_XUXRcXXwwmDTZzei2c1HAa7biyDUFW27zZfnODItfIFa_1Ye5oXCBGME7sTTtbp2hLasDP1XLrSQZeYlEp>  
includes videos, summaries, and links for you to learn more. Take note of  
the ones labeled ‚ÄúTry it now!‚Äù- many of these new announcements and  
features are ready to try out! Once you‚Äôve gotten to #100, you can test out  
your knowledge and take our quiz  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oioyGprTLq7o-XE01-d7w7KM0ndS5QhyQ2aDFAAQm4xlVSg91fsY77VBHuF7jsfrtKKfMvqaT5HghYoKL1BKtDiGCND9vYeXU7ypj2DSiBa3glLCDSO7C2w6Xc9y7INjGzC9fbUZCCH755JMtH4grv3iqRzsrHfNeiqAvlCguJ45cH3YBn1tnFCQ>  
to find out how well you know our I/O announcements about Search, Gemini,  
generative AI and beyond.

2.5 Flash-Lite + general availability of 2.5 Flash and Pro on Vertex AI ‚ú®

Gemini 2.5 Pro and Flash are now generally available on Vertex AI, offering  
faster, more scalable performance for enterprise use. We have also  
introduced Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite in public preview (our most cost-efficient  
model yet!) with support for supervised fine-tuning and native audio via  
the Live API. Learn more in this blog.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rTzoK5zlFWkxhjuWMKm7F8fubef8PzGqwvr0ey3cC9ir1tvLUVrF5MfbDFHKqcgQqK31-93q_g4DhpUyOvlYMdc2c-SQfVa7CfB4Us5jxckB9AQ1OIhJAAXRFEZ9deh-q_zUu2x9cqz67n2QrRbVPZgqDJpz__X7aR1ePE1RNhjEmIkSLr98cJRAEVAB42RkInmwhN95JxGDEz5F9MFwvh_vWNtzYaFdc6rQZHv-cukTslIAZlCHvPEQ_OGu4e7RHkBQ>

New G4 VMs with NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell üë©‚Äçüíª

Google Cloud just launched G4 VMs in preview  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5p1W_CiY6zE_wsDEr9Yjs3DxB4lqlCYCrAdFpF9h1ohiJvv2t0pfcqF_3HI8zHNdMLdrTVpkyY8oMyWCnsBBuNtSeEd__peNcFHhDtQd7xLXHogLkfPyTJbnhRoXVfQKpPz0NSqZSYP-xKksyyLSXKo4fUsgG7jCZAPUKVh7o32uUA0dDurQkwmgItM51oy90HRveFNi6KUHCcM5F5h4T6G6vfvKNfm3im-gBkGRtDx>-  
powered by NVIDIA‚Äôs new RTX Pro 6000 Blackwell GPUs. These machines offer a  
big boost in compute and memory, making them ideal for AI inference, 3D  
graphics, and simulation workloads. Now available in preview, with global  
rollout expected later this year.

Build Smart Apps with Ease: GenAI, Cloud SQL, and Observability for Faster  
Development

Master the essentials of building powerful gen AI applications.

In this session with Sujatha Mandava (Director, Product Management, SQL  
Databases Google Cloud) will explore the complete Gen AI application  
development lifecycle and demonstrate the new Application Design Center  
(ADC) for rapid app idea-to-deployment, alongside rich ecosystem  
integrations with frameworks like LangChain, LlamaIndex, and LangGraph, and  
the new MCP Toolbox for Databases for enhanced manageability and security  
of Gen AI agents. They'll also cover critical operational considerations,  
showcasing Cloud SQL Enterprise Plus features for performance, sub-second  
scalability, high availability, and disaster recovery.

July 15, 2025 11:00 AM - 12:00 AM PDT

<https://c.gle/ANiao5pbBF7yFD0MH8URzeOrfNAY3w5-2hw6UKntgeI4XNEZLJd2e4eD6Ap1Ns2TFlq6pCybcqJrKXSJqNMK2Ojse9OZBnHDLUuhnERrBPCeBUYyXXf53c8vv473xfs5v21MHs7QT51z01ij1HR3bHP_CcjSlZs_ZTYrOs6tOJ5a1kio-mcKcxIWrYB8cfCkWn7SXasu8ePWExz81Yq5rZyyqLl95c9dmFKd2yn8iwZfDU3sEOdTe6ZYgpw>

AI Innovators spotlight

A large group posing together to celebrate completing our AI workshop

Innovators

We have loved meeting so many innovators in person at our Build with AI  
workshops! üòç Not only are these events a great opportunity to meet and  
network fellow innovators, but you‚Äôll also get to learn about full stack of  
agent development, from data integration to final deployment and runtime  
with Google experts. Have you joined us in person for our Build With AI  
events yet? Join us for our upcoming event in Montreal on July 11th!  
Register here.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5of_pRFGs3pbOkAEaN5Dok8lQilso2Ub1p3AE1gkjSihJjW0YA-TJE-5Do3ib-ouWlO5C_nI4-qMI6n4MHPeCzljNDF394oFlkj_n-bgeAcXtecjpetuH9Cu1Tn1SHSgH1g7HOJjjEuldhMkS5RC5GhL7hiQtfQacb6W0n0Cm1-umCDsJ3HQCfKe7hPsGyRrFHUFmYtQS7DjYJUof9KpIPnPG9Y5aev6zABXyciiz4>

robot arm

Learn with Google AI

Learn how to build agents with Anthropic‚Äôs Claude on Vertex AI.

Join Anthropic and Google Cloud on June 25th at 3:00 PM PT for a technical  
session on building agents with Claude on Vertex AI. You'll learn to  
leverage MCP and Google's Agent Development Kit (ADK) for agent  
development, and get started with Claude Code. Register now!  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oK44dH0FOIqxXIK0icbur_Ikt6qxeH4FJg9DZQhvy_-uN8doIMLw-O4fwz44w0XOCqR_SCy9QK9GGH3JPiPpbp7Tc7E5QqMkqn8lcdnK_h87_Hr7hxl8WESV_juge9hkWGi9sP3PtWmzgPvm1Xo0YtIeVDLu9qI6yfcmIp0YVD_jhE-e69gCLzx4CxDBf1l7pAtWJjIPNAuQ>

Operationalize AI Agents.

Dive into the essential practices for operationalizing Generative AI Agents  
with Sokratis Kartakis and Sita Lakshmi Sangameswaran in this new video!  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qamFLpz7gOkzo5-DA1kudXh8D2YO9d1Tl-NDa7zBdi_8U1SBfT-qypiAQH5U1VI4xkSrfJ04Wt4IzTE2oQzifgfIPXhlv1uD2eriLL4G4FE_bxkBAYIhLigOUkwAd4JYJhnXyEoDOm6gXJvt4zJFx0lya-kf8Q66QSCXAZTXztbOxp10W8T8M>  
This comprehensive guide introduces AgentOps, building upon the foundations  
of DevOps, MLOps, and GenAIOps to tackle the unique challenges of managing  
AI agents. Learn the fundamental components including Agent evaluation,  
optimization, tool management, repository and CI/CD pipeline  
standardisation, and effective architecture designs incorporating people  
and processes.

How to create AI agents with Agent Development Kit (ADK).

Jason and Aja have taken their ‚ÄúReal Terms for AI‚Äù show on the road! In  
this episode,  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oaj8r75_wQqONHQh3XGi9dgTeGUTz2SkVLZDlTOpmo2rNc2aUYBD93SB7FKSPUeVzPnM56rfO1mUjtQpkeFRyJAVz73_9QEeNk3kxa1XfYOU5j8rAnLuKD5wCpSFGTtOGsajnRN2rN-OKij7VbuldWJLGJ5vXexrepBez-uNkjnsfOsvu4_Q>  
they chat with Dr. Fran Hinkelmann, who explains how ADK's model-agnostic,  
open-source approach provides tons of flexibility for developers. Learn how  
ADK helps structure tools using Python functions and classes, easily  
integrate with first and third-party tools like Google Maps, and offers  
built-in support for Model Context Protocol (MCP) to standardize LLM  
interactions. Plus, see how the dev UI and Vertex AI Agent Engine  
streamline development and deployment.

Tracing & Fixing Emergent Misalignment


OpenAI's researchers identified an internal activation pattern linked to misaligned personas in language models and showed it can be detected and dampened through targeted retraining, hinting at an early‚Äêwarning system for alignment drift.


The results in the given article, suggest that language models can represent a variety of personas, including a misaligned persona, presumably as a result of training on diverse internet text. They identified a pattern in the model‚Äôs internal activations corresponding to this misaligned persona.


When they fine-tune on datasets of incorrect answers in narrow domains, that amplifies this pattern, leading to generalized misalignment. When they fine-tune on datasets of correct answers, it suppresses this pattern leading to re-alignment of an emergently misaligned model. Read more [https://blog.codewithahsan.dev/r/f2d82d18?m=1a5dac5f-993e-493a-82e4-3b7f55ca6c58]

The Component Dev Kit of Angular


The @angular/cdk refers to the Angular Component Dev Kit (CDK), a collection of tools and utilities for building UI components in Angular applications. It provides a set of behavior primitives and foundational services that are unopinionated about their presentation, meaning they don't include any specific styling like Material Design.


The CDK serves as a base layer of well-tested functionality upon which developers can build their own custom components with unique styling. It includes modules for various common application features and UI patterns, such as:


 * Accessibility (A11y): Utilities for improving the accessibility of components, including focus management and screen reader support.
 * Drag and Drop: Functionality for creating interactive drag-and-drop interfaces with features like sorting, transferring items, and custom previews.
 * Overlay: Tools for dynamically displaying floating content, such as dialogs, tooltips, and pop-ups, with flexible positioning options.
 * Scrolling: Utilities for managing scroll events and implementing virtual scrolling for large lists.
 * Table: A configurable component for displaying tabular data, including features like sorting and trackBy for performance optimization.
 * Tree: Directives and components for building hierarchical content as expandable trees.







Angular Material
UI component infrastructure and Material Design components for Angular web applications.


Angular Material

Kysely - The type-safe SQL Query Builder for TypeScript


Kysely is a type-safe SQL query builder for TypeScript. It allows developers to write SQL queries within their TypeScript code, ensuring type safety and autocompletion, thus reducing errors during development and improving code maintainability.

Essentially, it acts as a layer between TypeScript and the database, enabling developers to interact with databases using a more intuitive and type-safe approach compared to raw SQL strings.

Most Organizations Failing to Deliver on Developer Experience and DevOps Maturity


Disconnect between the promise of engineering excellence and the day-to-day realities inside most software teams is growing, according to The State of Software Engineering Excellence 2025 from Harness.


The study exposes critical failures across the software delivery lifecycle, costing companies millions in lost productivity and stifled innovation. Despite widespread commitment to improve DevOps practices, most organizations are falling short, unable to deliver on the developer experience and best practices needed to compete in today's digital landscape.


The report offers a clear look at where many software teams are still struggling to scale core engineering capabilities:


 * 67% of software teams cannot build and test their development environment within 15 minutes.
 * 64% of infrastructure code deployments still rely on manual steps.
 * 61% of engineering leaders say code reviews take over a day to complete.
 * 55% of build pipelines lack proper quality gates.
 * 52% of engineering teams do not have key tools to support incident management.
 * 50% of application deployments still rely on manual processes.

subject: What happens when governments cut health aid
mail:
Two updates on what's at stakehttps://gatesnot.es/46eVqGU  

What happens when governments cut health aid https://gatesnot.es/3Gam5tZ 

https://gatesnot.es/3Gam5tZ  

By Bill Gates https://gatesnot.es/3Gam5tZ| June 27, 2025 

I‚Äôve been giving speeches about vaccines for 25 years. After all that time, it could have become routine. But it never has.

One reason is that vaccines are still one of the most miraculous tools we have. The other is the moment we‚Äôre in right now.

This year, the number of children dying may rise for the first time this century. That‚Äôs because governments are pulling back on global health funding‚Äîincluding support for Gavi, a public-private partnership that has helped halve childhood deaths in the world‚Äôs poorest countries. 

At a summit in Brussels this week, I gave a speech about what that would mean, and why it‚Äôs never been more important to keep investing in vaccines.

You can read my full remarks to Gavi on Gates Notes now https://gatesnot.es/3Gam5tZ.    

I also just submitted written testimony to Congress about a related threat: sweeping cuts that have been proposed to America‚Äôs health aid budget‚Äîand their very real, and very deadly, consequences. 

That testimony, given to the Senate Appropriations Committee, is up on my blog now https://gatesnot.es/44jTkTA as well.    

My message right now is simple: Health aid saves lives. When it gets cut, people die. 

Stay tuned for more updates on the fight to get this funding restored.

subject: Claude masters blackmail, Karpathy‚Äôs rule, and 90% faster AWS cold starts
mail:
( https://www.gitpod.io/?utm_campaign=the_workspace_newsletter&utm_source=Customerio&utm_medium=Email )

Gitpod Newsletter ‚Äì June 26 2025

June 26, 2025

******************************************************************************
Claude learns about blackmail, Karpathy's rule, and 90% faster AWS cold starts
******************************************************************************

00:00 | 15:23

The AI boom has passed the "neat demo" phase. Autonomous agents are now fixing kernel bugs, blackmailing red-teamers, and flooding repos with code you didn't write. Whether that ends in a productivity renaissance or a security headline depends on one thing: how safely your machines can write and run code.

TL;DR

‚Ä¢

ICYMI ‚Üí Ona early access: Privacy-first software-engineering agents inside your VPC. Request early access.

‚Ä¢

Agents can be the breach. Anthropic shows LLMs will leak data on command; isolated, auditable workspaces are no longer optional.

‚Ä¢

90% faster cold-starts, zero egress. New image-caching and in-VPC agents mean more shipping, less waiting, and no data leaving your perimeter.

‚Ä¢

Meet us IRL: Learn how real teams are scaling AI agents at our session at AWS Summit NYC on July 16 ( https://www.gitpod.io/aws-nyc-2025 ).

Happy reading!

---------------
Ecosystem watch
---------------

When the agent becomes the insider threat ( https://www.anthropic.com/research/agentic-misalignment )
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Anthropic's red-team convinced LLM agents to blackmail users and exfiltrate data. Security focus is shifting from leaky humans to rogue code-writers, making disposable, audited environments inside the corporate perimeter less of a best practice and more table stakes.

"Low-background steel" for human-only datasets ( https://blog.jgc.org/2025/06/low-background-steel-content-without-ai.html )
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

John Graham-Cumming revives a nuclear-physics metaphor to predict a premium market for 100 % human-written text, untouched by model feedback loops. Provenance and tamper-proof audit trails are poised to become competitive advantages, not compliance footnotes.

Code researcher outsmarts the kernel ( https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/Code_Researcher-1.pdf )
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Microsoft Research built an AI agent that automatically fixed more than half of Linux kernel crashes‚Äîno humans required. The agent spots problems by analyzing past code changes, runs thorough tests, and iteratively rebuilds software until it's stable.

Karpathy's Golden Rule: intern-proof your agents ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LCEmiRjPEtQ )
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Andrej Karpathy advises treating LLMs like crash-prone interns: sandbox them, insist on tiny, test-backed diffs, and gate everything through CI. In other words, the path to safe autonomy runs straight through ephemeral, policy-enforced development environments.

"Vibe coding" comes with a safety label ( https://blog.alexmaccaw.com/how-to-vibe-code-as-a-senior-engineer/ )
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Alex MacCaw argues that vibe coding‚Äîshipping code you haven't fully read‚Äîonly works if you fence the model with explicit rules, ample context, and tight CI hooks. Without guardrails, it's a fast track to spaghetti code and tech debt.

--------------------------------------
ICYMI: Upcoming launches & new stories
--------------------------------------

Ona, your privacy-first software engineering agent ( https://www.gitpod.io/solutions/ai )
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Run privacy-first SWE agents entirely inside your VPC‚Äîyour code, keys, and logs never cross the firewall. Each Ona agent spins up a sandboxed, disposable environment in your cloud, tackling hundreds of tasks in parallel and handing changes back to you in your IDE with a single click. Request early access (Gitpod enterprise users receive access sooner!).

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Start instantly with pre-configured dev environments on high-spec CPUs/GPUs, without any infrastructure setup. Join the waitlist ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/coming-soon-gitpod-as-a-saas#:~:text=Gitpod%2Dhosted%20compute.-,Feature%20waitlist,-Email ) to get early access.

Mind the AI security gap ( https://www.gitpod.io/whitepaper/ai-security-gap )
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Most AI pilots stall‚Äînot due to model failures, but insecure infrastructure. This paper dives into overlooked threats in AI-assisted development and outlines pragmatic security principles like including isolated environments and VPC-bound AI agents, for safe enterprise adoption.

AI agents need infrastructure (and that's now your problem) ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/ai-agents-need-infrastructure )
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A candid look at why letting autonomous agents roam free on laptops will end in shadow AI" drama. We outline a safer pattern: pre-provisioned, policy-enforced environments where every human or agent action is logged, sandboxed, and instantly disposable.

From our engineers: How we accelerated dev container startups by 90% ( https://www.gitpod.io/blog/automating-dev-container-image-caching )
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Learn how automated ECR-layer caching pipelines cut environment boot times by optimizing container layers‚Äîwithout YAML adjustments or added costs.

New security features for your plan
We are updating our free and paid plans to make your team's workdays more pleasant and productive. All plans now come with enhanced security, and paid plans include powerful AI functionalities.
LEARN MORE [https://slack.com/x-t5931519823363-9111366555042/blog/news/june-2025-pricing-and-packaging-announcement?t=learn_more]
What does this mean for you?

You are a member of a workspace currently on a free Slack plan. The following security features have been added to your Slack plan:

- Limit how long members are signed in to Slack with session duration
- Enforce security policies with built-in native device management

Along with these additional security features, free teams can continue to collaborate seamlessly‚Äìcommunicate with internal and external teams, share clips, capture notes, and manage action items‚Äìall in one place.

You can unlock AI features, unlimited message history, group huddles and more by switching to a Slack paid plan. Visit our plans page [https://slack.com/x-t5931519823363-9111366555042/pricing?t=pricing_page] to review or change your plan.

EXPLORE CHANGES [https://slack.com/x-t5931519823363-9111366555042/help/articles/39264531104275?t=explore_changes]

subject: The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud: June 26
mail:
The overwhelmed person‚Äôs guide to Google Cloud By Richard Seroter  
<mailto:rseroter@google.com>

New and shiny

Just launched! Gemini is coming to your terminal.

Yesterday, we announced Gemini CLI, an open-source AI agent designed to  
bring the capabilities of Gemini directly to developers' terminals. Create  
complete applications, add features, generate docs, deploy software and do  
a million other things. It‚Äôs open source, with nearly unlimited usage‚Äî60  
queries per minute!‚Äî of Gemini 2.5 Pro and its 1 million token context  
window. Getting started is simple: just log in with a Google account to  
create and use a free Gemini Code Assist license. Try the Gemini CLI now!  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5ozBLNnIrsWr2rWNr-_hK3X5BJIXNFFEX7fDoLPVyZiRtVAHsJYKB-3eO_Hlt_BPiHDy_YdvrknAc0JxsMrVWLo4vL89Sz95PlM8G8Hpwr2_C_EhkRNkATe9a9KLbC6ZbSL9Ok-nm1vKLq1vQNrPFC7y7NwOe2D7S3XEQm9d4m1_kb0Igyg>

Agent Development Kit v1.3.0 released.

Just a couple weeks back, v1.2.0 came out, so you know this team is cooking  
right now. Version 1.2.0 added Vertex AI Agent Engine as a deployment  
option via the CLI (blog example here  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qVEsd4zAp5KiX88wvmIGYDfy0KD8e8r74n_svXjnJ10n7LPa0z59BYt_-MAzw3u5xUFtMqeXF8NFZWrF3XNi6RgDDd3RdUTbzM-Zz0SUB27SPvUWKFEK9sa1k5MqyK_48riOTk9VuxVQwICmV64sj58EuD_iC-1OLU2Yw4EeRsV5-dL9jMxhOCA-LnCb70XFdlEor-vtPK3X4TcQRz5P3VGJV5QGtoyxIH8gaP0NftQrSHJwe7bRuPQHgeakM4Lg>)  
among other features. And now version 1.3.0 has some terrific Dev UI  
improvements and a new tool for looking up content at a given URL. See the  
release notes.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rV6UuN1YHPNTwAcSe5-FVIsnfU3EGHHjWeSwCs5J_sj_oaYs0CuQFq2Wz74eUyKcJXwVSz7j5L3ZNVNLOFi1wc0yJ21oXquUHqUP4bto7TUFfJ-4wWYjmb_phG80zFouRw2g7n5Y9aTZ19K1Zo9iCRUuEACwlsfCI1B6zKWblXEWxZq49EiVKIQIcfDg>

Business glossaries in the Dataplex Universal Catalog are now GA.

Manage key terminology and definitions across your company using a  
glossary. It supports hierarchies, connections between terms, and the  
ability to link your data resources to terms in the glossary. Check out the  
blog post.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5r4Ol8946se9sAb7f4xP1NX5anK69asbvxQCiTiT1Sg_2oimrcnmf-BT64azM0QIVlBLctBlYsuvz3d6itZ8G0EwE6iJmXNhgw5YxIPVZBeYmc2YJVeBQaqYioBFvVB0gtpvQ59cnr06g9Vutk6w9g2FSQrHaFppORKbm2JZojdiu51GODoMeo9591QB_6tvHr4nuqXc9LPMAtk8SxOu6lXb37g7nVBGNVLfL_DvLcjGWAI>

Don‚Äôt look now, but Gemini Code Assist is getting easier to use. Actually,  
look now.

This team is now shipping weekly and I‚Äôve noticed. They've been working  
hard to add functionality and reduce friction for developers. Now you can  
configure exclude files to limit what shows up in context, add code  
snippets to the chat context, add terminal output to the chat context,  
enjoy automatic scrolling of chat responses, click on file names in the  
chat response, and even stop a chat response mid-answer. Browse the release  
notes  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rzrsC5zMLq83lDEWgolzybRGlN7Jg9U9-o-BSAoX7-wZNuGmcvpYEO7NGk1beJnuUgB55xPcfiBHp5fbIfX5WmiNHCImJNLsfVicVgTB2tGPMp_TtNEGruzCpUVWShL6TtrOwBvw_2gXk3xm19IBnixRYq03kPCMLMFseaNm7L8PrTi-Hpji1wJ49ArcirhwzLNTiT>  
and read our latest blog post.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oJXU0C09A1Pykv_1DkguoOg1VhvXHyl8yK-sNZktjkZpecq7T6WEuhHTC9IIc66D5X_esv3HSu7Ld1pxEYDg8DzqKMwaJtb75gC7BwePE0dvQnkSNDYuRhrL3L7cxdBwWsxZ4GX0V5s9DlSRQ4sjiAeXJFH2PswmrEzqyuruQvyKyzD9NJ1uE0cS7EqZuwYHr4t4Mqpkxi3bNaUAZj4LBy8zJM8Nk>

Join us in Montreal, Quebec on July 11th for an intensive, hands-on  
workshop: Build with AI: Building Production-Ready, Full-Stack AI Agents  
with Gemini 2.5 and Google's Latest Frameworks. This workshop is your  
opportunity to dive deep into building sophisticated single and multi-agent  
systems using the powerful Gemini 2.5 and Google's cutting-edge open-source  
framework, the Agent Development Kit (ADK). Don't miss this opportunity to  
transform your AI development skills! Register here!  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rvR51IJx8dee8RnKCJoxKkq2li-JOYhVcvE2jppNAEwXuKLot1baLusXu_6DZsY9L2s0ImKfOIhRjgbEl8fz6mmzeAmJez1XA9-kxm5Rq7dSJPoAQ0VVOA_vhDb1QLCSzwvBLJTt9_jmE6zTw-lndVGv_uoT1Kt9hGNVAebCYdlJFr9Skj>

Watch this

Operationalizing AI agents.

It‚Äôs a long video, but this is an under-served topic and deserves a deep  
dive. Watch this (or ask Gemini to summarize it) to learn about various  
management considerations for your AI agent architecture.

A captured graphic of a Google Cloud video where Sita and Sokratis look at  
the many operational considerations for an AI agent architecture.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5o7cPwvZYNCmtCudiCiV6z6FrM3EIISOvepHaNGnM0y8xpsPCtdSM-1LGibyWMzQYW8bo_3OBBgLCSOS2WgaVr-_ReU3RR2DAPD9BKz6Lr-qN3jPie0RaWYaIEQvMKS9u_v-Zm5xhb6tFtcomLMHKGqJRedCYdgZg>

Community cuts

Learning to use Vertex AI to train a model.

Vertex AI does a lot of things. It‚Äôs almost easy to forget that you can  
train models with it! Kavisha crafted a useful post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qn-A6s-mAAkzAE9zdsfpZZzeXlxJVecbYE0QPZXMJPtjekEZ-TcPbdCdT2H_sOIvCJRnpl0JrMq_jQYceXRR0IKpVs0Q8USpW5Zzmnqe0ZuAdptTcqDteINAMmZjiGS_XRq9leth2rgsCDBPXlebqzqlEdxVTnZiGgTLa0SsAxQ4HaqQ7FGqgHL8pccaezEk1IN6-IcFdDGmPL32IuXsUST6U1wZVR6KZG8fQjBLgF-VJKOcQ4Sehb2ap0PVKQRnuEI8w>  
that walks us through a simple but representative example using AutoML.

One-click deployment of Gemma to Cloud Run.

How easy is this? Geshan shows us  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rvyfnOWy_EemGxSPURJLO2frK1iUh6VzBLi6BjFEpaPjbeeqOM4aCK4xtRzcRohZ48xPgB-_Cd9Z75QAiusr718LaM51rHu4Dx2qnrcXrMgeAQt5GFBhTwStfNjYhY45rFM_QV2VPAd8Hljc_yoAaf5OiU5zuOVB1VWKV-tzkMDJrRvy-t2Kmo6ZmX7HvM>  
how to take the open Gemma model and deploy it to Cloud Run directly from  
Google AI Studio. Doesn‚Äôt get any easier than that.

Using Gemini Code Assist to help with DevOps tasks.

A coding assistant is also useful for people who aren‚Äôt software  
developers. Gerardo published this post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oTJ16NNv-X11snFJip7KBPbFBsHW0NSbJIg4ZJfxjfLupYIMVa6rguSTMzeR_wp4ihvBhUWfXcc-H7DlMcXDGnrVLkxSePLgNXsC0PbhH6jodCESB83Y3k31XNh6_iVuMAwMs58jjpv_Z6rSJzzXchF3ULJ8ZeYrPIgRCH2Mp7m02V3DfofOZCNeiDrD5mX36Ux3I-KIT1sJqh_lqBci4j_6Yx11GSifxgwnJ0YS1VmLkpuahCWFuPjHsLmF-XBWGr8Yt7b-t1zxaE8XN8f2RE>  
showing how this tool helped optimize his Terraform code.

Learn and grow

Give your AI agents easy access to BigQuery datasets.

The MCP Toolbox for Databases makes it simpler to interact with a wide  
range of databases. This codelab  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5qQvFIWRI_u5AxoJKS0MXYvxyFC62dduygYFuZw4Bdbt_iUEYIBYvvBqTSJ9lvBfaecxeSJH_OCxdfmDSu4vpAaspRSRiDejeOV6KFlcoQ9TSERgo4JbkFvVr4jFB5GPyaeOrsplxh7Dm3aDC7qJKvBLNd-j1wYrPdtwK4FJJ3qQn-DWAFyrLIw8mJgvhE44JjAgiAJRAOyJzrPWGsQUvk>  
shows you how to point the Toolbox at BigQuery.

Let‚Äôs get smarter about IAM service accounts.

If this is only part one, this should end up being an outstanding blog  
series. Read this one  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5raBwb6U6nXlIy6giwhaAWhV9r7NS6PKrUuOW175t1f13jOuNnZ8lu8HNS08gZ23SiVv9bPHGWNNWBOP4p2d8JZwdrwd2tv7vbRUD6F0pQnfDORvO7tp4GUkOXBpBzXEcZ357umMMyMn8ValkSEdwev4qQqa_xaLroQwgJzA05HgDDAf8rjYy5nrnfevTh0epgKvQHbd6klNyCt4XXb7i8W9dcNJP9Zdz9UuIu-csciL7O2EHmZ>  
to learn about the best ways to use service accounts. As a bonus, check out  
the new roles and permission interface in the docs.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5omkELJ4jowST8M5Os5hkD2tntkP-aohIBt7veAQqNRVU9ywhrlDR4-07frs8dU3m1DBnJ1MSQlNgJqD-N6wmyJ8IAyW5gAjQEwB9hKkj5sdFNmixESQwa8Jb0Vl_Vw7_i84jvIrc1DIjvaQqi9a0_RVXm2Qkm8YfptwhQlSlZf2MpTuD86>

Pick a pattern, any pattern.

Most problems have a few possible solutions. Megan wrote an excellent blog  
post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oRAB_FlcQt_XjJ2A1Y5bbJxLeeyrr-923fDkJ76oNjIx5rj9GAsW2XGrQsYjyP4tz7V0Hp-G8MiXmSc9QWvQvJmJAdqholKNTbqx0a6sqpemCczAzDzDFDo1Neh8xEksYKqWZ-DMjohnXWmDsRqAFE1Tq951-WEyHKbi8gS6-b20Ph_BkE0AcpMkGz8zKBzlZD5Gn8x9tjI-d_BKPPZNggw6qzALWUZlNhRWe-KvrHvoEkuD1RzeoUQQ>  
that takes an agent scenario and proposes five valid agent patterns to  
solve it.

Build your evaluation skills.

You, or someone you know, should be investing in AI evals. I liked this  
blog post  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rryNBELKDZLUg7hcaRG0DlQNQ_MMXusgohZqxxH9_HcvpMXG__GbIrOlRzAuQLPXPWZc4OjxpBdEPp5TFFycBCeOQ7JF9w6wfealtXjz_Klv70PZTIx2_Pw1XN4r13Twdg3Kb92x1uIi8GPXy3qfarw8cm37ivb9piBbJ2iq40AfUJlWTv0nTXRYXDltKdu6B9FmBgcfmjw_U-m59jCTW7c_UcraP36Wu9OOpH4HyVzy0GiEcW2lEjz6A>  
which looked at different types of evals, and how the Gen AI evaluation  
service in Vertex AI offers a path forward.

One more thing

The Live API is such a powerful feature of the Gemini model. Read this new  
guide.

Building more interactive AI systems? Get fresh code samples and guidance  
in this documentation.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5o-3zhFi05vkefgkebKlKieXVp2cLcJJECKy34qCCNzPt6Yku0wKZB8Nxj0WCOQp4dbThWLD9bIk3JHHBmx5-1qrRaV7nhiNIsGkQ32ImPuyIRdcRlA-JX4AMHfSTVZQwm2ogRtCNr9jKOBbGX8HBpJQ5Us7P4Z4QsqKIvD6y4d5WMw6iU>

An X post from Philipp Schmid that points us to new documentation for the  
interactive Gemini Live API.  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5pnACNWuJK3d5Wy_JdnDSdlrTUylqrlXzsZEvxQtuesD66Q7xEQAVDp1Xlb6yigVHZwW7ECCYe1tDoniiV0ySwO_zGQLeougNUwG6wkwsfh7Z5uv_fdap9HiUK8t4byoea6ZXQbw_d7AJ9XqVTAHjUp2_F7OjrlmthwxGci0KlLdds0RA>

Follow us on Social media.

Add your voice to the conversation and get the latest news, views, and  
insights.

X  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5peDHK7x3GWZt0WmoqK5dQw13EljHMxptyEVTid5bjM0KErIpU2mK4CE6ImrH9QdbV-4nGqLXK_h3cI3LAab228fmA5l28GSIyH6VzJlMZcnC4tPtoxMXUSH7ar1C7Zqh7g4yWjO2w3xWe17M9OxS3wEZ0LzBdwDIjx8sUSqvD0hNQqv1ZnLd_II9TJzCA>

Google Cloud blog  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5rKcW4U1q6lr-x2bh6kAYx2ezAU01_N9_KmYB51Y0Jez06mi9DEcRS3sI_tpVVtL8vKsDuZPmiRcn36vBnzxLQoZJdBiozizful2pEqGRWkUihN_lqOkaPBkSxQowl7>

LinkedIn  
<https://c.gle/ANiao5oU4rznf0n02bPbaIm0TB-PHopqhXAVdgR6Z366ivwj8rxffy71StO9WadOO8Ep4_z7mU9b0PWT7yXeVY-fuV44oSeTthqo_R5YRO0eLy7BFrNDUfXrX2wxjQd2SRAZ6uucOG7C1IRAMvmz66UxwzfU66cU>

Facebook

subject: Introducing Warp 2.0 | Code now in the Agentic Development Environment
mail:
Warp 2.0 - The First Agentic Development Environment

¬†

( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9BRhSbVSpI )
Today, we're excited to launch Warp 2.0, the Agentic Development Environment. Warp 2.0 is an evolution from an intelligent terminal to an all-in-one workbench built to support full-lifecycle development with agents.

In Warp 2.0, you get:

* The top overall coding agent: #1 on Terminal-Bench and 71% on SWE-bench Verified
* Agent multi-threading and management with the ability to run and monitor multiple agents ‚Äì all under your control
* The best interface for agentic development: from our Universal Input to our inline code editor ‚Äì Warp 2.0 is the first workbench designed for developing by prompt

----------------------
What's new in Warp 2.0
----------------------

State-of-the-art coding agent, with a built-in code editor

Warp‚Äôs coding agent scored 71% on SWE-bench Verified and ranks #1 on Terminal-Bench (52%) - making it the best overall coding agent in the world. Prompt the agent, watch it gather context and create a plan; as the agent runs, it will loop you in if it needs help ‚Äì and you can make edits directly in our inline code editor.

Multi-thread yourself with agents

Run and manage multiple agents natively within Warp. Prompt agents, attach context, and watch them build features, fix bugs, and resolve crashing servers. Grant them full autonomy or limit what they can do ‚Äì you have full control of their actions. Track progress in Warp's agent management pane.

Still the best command-line

Warp still has the best terminal UX on the market. All the innovations that make Warp powerful ‚Äì our rich editor for commands, our block based output ‚Äì work as they always have, and are now usable in guiding agents, not just writing commands.

Shared context for humans and agents

By virtue of Warp's low layer in the stack and its built-in knowledge base, Warp Drive, it's easy for your teammates ‚Äì AI and human ‚Äì to do any task. In addition, Warp's agents have access to MCP, rules, and anything that can be gathered by running a CLI, which is pretty much anything.

--------------
More AI, on us
--------------

To celebrate Warp 2.0, we're increasing AI request limits for all paid users:

* Pro: 1,000 ‚Üí 2,500/month
* Turbo: 3,000 ‚Üí 10,000/month (+ unlimited Lite requests)
* Pay-as-you-go available after you use your monthly quota

------------------
Try Warp 2.0 today
------------------

Download Warp ( https://app.warp.dev/get_warp? )

Open Warp ( warp://auth/desktop_redirect )

Get the deep-dive on features, philosophy, and demos on our blog ( https://www.warp.dev/blog ).

P.S. Tag us or use #AgenticDevelopmentEnvironment on
X ( https://x.com/warpdotdev ),
Bluesky ( https://bsky.app/profile/warp.dev ),
LinkedIn ( https://linkedin.com/company/warpdotdev/ ), or
TikTok ( https://www.tiktok.com/@warp.dev ).
Check out our communities on Discord ( https://discord.gg/warpdotdev ), Reddit ( https://www.reddit.com/r/warpdotdev/ ), and Slack ( https://join.slack.com/t/warpcommunity/shared_invite/zt-37gkd88iq-KY1~_7VTDiUbs7g3kt3__g ). We'll share our favorites!

Warp is the intelligent terminal with AI and your dev team's knowledge built-in.

AI has a resilience problem: Designers and researchers can fix it
AI has a resilience

problem: Designers

and researchers can fix it

‚Ää
AI has made incredible strides, but it still struggles with one crucial element: resilience. When technology doesn't account for the unpredictability of human lives, things start to get messy. From missed medical appointments to flawed predictions, the problem is fundamental in how the technology is designed. But designers and researchers are in a unique position to fix this. By embracing complexity and integrating user feedback, learn how AI can be more responsive to the real-world challenges.

Designing AI with resilience: Fixing the messy realities of human life with UX

While AI technology has revolutionized many industries, it still struggles to meet the unpredictable, messy realities of human life. While AI excels in idealized scenarios or ‚Äúhappy paths,‚Äù it often fails when real-life complexities arise. Examples range from failed suicide prevention algorithms to public ticketing systems that malfunction due to an inability to account for nuances. To solve this we must embrace resilience, and designers and researchers play a pivotal role.

For truly adaptive AI, UX design must focus on real-world complexity, shifting from seamless user experiences to those that accept failure, friction, and feedback. By making AI systems responsive to change and integrating data more meaningfully, designers can ensure technology helps people when we need it the most, in unexpected situations. Clearly, designing AI for resilience isn‚Äôt just about enhancing usability; it‚Äôs about ensuring technology works when life doesn‚Äôt go as planned.

** Online this September
------------------------------------------------------------

Hi HUZAIR2024,

We would like to support our community and provide an opportunity to apply for a Scholarship to attend the TechLead 2025, which will be held online!

If you know someone who might be interested in applying for a scholarship, please share the following form with them. Or if you think it's relevant to you, feel free to fill out the form!

All the necessary information about scholarships can be found in the form.

Topics to be covered:
* Career growth (skills, productivity, salary increase process) in the AI era
* interviews, interviewing people (how to interview for AI/LLM skills, deal with thousands of applications using AI)
* Ethics / ethical implications of AI use in hiring, applying, automation processes
* Strategies for Integrating Non-deterministic Systems
* Addressing Technical Debt and the Impact of AI Tools
* Analyzing Failure Modes and Incident Management Strategies

https://forms.gle/scPy3aWakGCCjjXF8?utm_source=GitNation+Conferences&utm_campaign=7497428afd-TL25_scholarship%2Bcfp_10%2F06%2F25&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_-788ab96665-568319264&mc_cid=7497428afd&mc_eid=UNIQID

subject: Remember the 80/20 Rule?
mail:
Perfectionism is Procrastination.Dear Huzair, following on the last note I sent you.

Perfectionism is another way of saying procrastination and I've been there.

Another tweak the banner, headline, add another certification.

The 80-20 rule (The Pareto principle) says that 80% of outcomes come from 20% of inputs.

In our case, if your profile is 80% done, move on the content because content is the vehicle that's going to get you in front of clients and prospects.

So:

No more tweaking, your personal brand is 80% there, you're done.
Move on to content.

Then you move onto Sales (DM's and closing).

LinkedIn doesn‚Äôt reward great ideas, it rewards visibility and the odds are in your favour as Google and AI search engines all scan LinkedIn, it's considered a trusted source, alongside Wikipedia, IMDB and a few others.

You can have the smartest offer, the deepest insight, the most life-changing solution.

But if nobody knows you, nobody can spend money with you.

If you‚Äôre still stuck with your message, rewriting your profile, or watching others win while you overthink it all ‚Äî let‚Äôs fix it.

That‚Äôs exactly what we diagnose (and fix) with our Personal Branding Online Course, you can learn more about it and sign up here https://theinacademy.com/linkedin-business-profile-2024.

Just a sharp, honest look at why things aren‚Äôt converting ‚Äî and a clear path forward that 

**actually works** in 2025.

**P.S.** The longer you hide behind ‚Äúworking on it,‚Äù the more you delay the growth that‚Äôs ready for you, this is an opportunity to change that from "To Do" to "Done".

**Cheers**

Faisal

subject: Launch Log 3: MCP goes GA, Smarter Agents, and Image Context
mail:
********************
Launch Log 3 is here
********************

MCP is now on GA, and we've overhauled the process for editing agent-generated content. And our Preview build now supports uploading images as context and suggests prompts to save based on your recent Agent interactions

Check out the blog ( https://www.warp.dev/blog/launch-log-3 ) for more details.

( https://youtu.be/ja6dZwWgtd8 )

*****************************
MCP support is fully launched
*****************************

Last Launch Log we shared MCP on Preview‚Äî thank you to everyone who provided feedback. Based on that input, we‚Äôve incorporated improvements and are excited to bring MCP to GA.

Add MCP servers to Warp to allow agents to interact with external data sources. We've been using it to debug Sentry errors, pull information from Notion, and connect to Postgres.

‚Ää

*****************************
Refine Agent Mode suggestions
*****************************

Refine agent-generated commands.¬†Take another pass through the commands agents create, asking Warp to add feature flags or change commit messages.

‚Ää

*******************
New to Warp Preview
*******************

Attach images as prompt context.¬†Upload an image alongside your Prompt, and Warp will include it as context.¬†

Warp will suggest Prompts for you to save. Prompt chips will show up after your Agent conversations, suggestion reusable prompts.

Thanks for using Warp, and let us know what you think on X ( https://x.com/warpdotdev ), by joining our Community Slack ( https://go.warp.dev/join-preview ), or by filing a GitHub ( https://github.com/warpdotdev/Warp ) issue.

Happy coding,

The Warp Team
